{"title_page": "Tanguturi Anjaiah", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Tanguturi Anjaiah\n| image =Tanguturi Anjayya statue.jpg \n| caption =Statue of Tanguturi Anjayya\n| birth_date = 1919\n| birth_place = [[Hyderabad State]], [[India]]\n| residence = [[Bhanoor]], [[Hyderabad, Telangana|Hyderabad]], [[Telangana]], India\n| death_date = 1986 (aged 67 years)\n| death_place =\n| order        = 7th\n| office       = Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh\n| constituency =\n| term_start   = 11 October 1980\n| term_end     = 24 February 1982\n| predecessor  = [[Marri Chenna Reddy]]\n| successor    = [[Bhavanam Venkatarami Reddy]]\n| constituency_MP1 = [[Secunderabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Secunderabad]]\n| parliament1  = Indian\n| term_start1  = 31 December 1984\n| term_end1    = 27 November 1986\n| predecessor1 = [[P. Shiv Shankar]]\n| successor1   = [[T. Manemma]]\n| party =[[Congress (I)]]\n| religion = [[Hinduism]]\n| spouse = [[T. Manemma]]\n| children = 1 son and 4 daughters\n| website =\n| footnotes =|\n| year = |\n|image_upright=}}\n'''Tanguturi Anjaiah'''  (1919\u20131986) was the 7th [[Chief Minister]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]], India, from October 1980 to February 1982.\n\n==Early life==\nTanguturi Anjaiah, known as T. Anjaiah alias Ramakrishna Reddy Talla was born on August 16, 1919. His parents belonged to Bhanoor village in Medak district. Anjaiah studied at Sultan Bazar high school. He couldn't pursue further education after matriculation due to financial difficulties so he started working at [[Hyderabad Allwyn]] for a daily wage of 6 anna (equal to 24 pice).\n\nAnjaiah faced many adversities in his early life which made him a fighter for the cause of social justice.\n\n==Career==\nT. Anjaiah rose from a being worker at [[Hyderabad Allwyn Limited]] in [[Hyderabad State|Hyderabad]] to become a trade union leader and later Union Labour Minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/article3090281.ece|title=YSR to unveil Anjaiah's statue on August 16|author=|date=14 August 2006|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nT. Anjaiah was nominated by the ruling party to replace [[Marri Chenna Reddy]] as Chief Minister on 11 October 1980. At the time of nomination, Anjaiah was the union minister of state for Labour. Anjaiah inducted all 15 dissident members of Chenna Reddy cabinet and formed the biggest state ministry the country had ever known.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/2004/03/26/stories/2004032604711300.htm|title=The Hindu : POLL-POURRI|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> He reduced it to 45 member on advice of center.\n\nAs the [[Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh]], he was known for his accommodating politics.\n\nThe two young uprising politicians at that time, Dr. [[Y. S. Rajasekhara Reddy]] and [[N. Chandrababu Naidu]], gained importance during Anjaiah's term as Chief Minister. A proposal to make [[N. T. Rama Rao|NTR]] a member of the Rajya Sabha did the rounds during this time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/52008486/Humanists-Chief-Ministers-I-Met|title=Humanists Chief Ministers I Met|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> Anjaiah was a mentor of [[P. Janardhan Reddy]].\n\nT. Anjaiah faced opponents including some of the ministers in his party after the ruling party lost Municipal elections in Visakhapatnam and Vijayawada. Asked by Mrs. Gandhi to step down on February 13, Anjiah tendered his resignation officially seven days later on February 20, 1982. Anjiah as a leader without followers could evoke unimaginable public sympathy. At his last public appearance as the chief minister, the day before he resigned Anjaiah was cheered by a 30,000-strong crowd. C. Jagannath Rao, who served in his cabinet as a home minister recalls him as, \"Whatever one may say against him, his remarkable simplicity endeared him to the people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/andhra-pradesh-cm-tanguturi-anjiah-unceremoniously-fired-by-congress-high-command/1/391472.html|title=Andhra Pradesh CM Tanguturi Anjiah unceremoniously fired by Congress high command|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Bhavanam Venkatarami Reddy]] replaced T. Anjaiah on February 24, 1982. [[Bhavanam Venkatarami Reddy]] himself was a dissident minister in the Marri Chenna Reddy ministry. T. Anjaiah was elected as Member of Parliament in 1984 from Secundrabad constituency.\n\n==Notable work ==\nT. Anjaiah's earliest act as Chief Minister was to conduct elections to the Panchayati Raj bodies and Municipalities. It was the first time the Sarpanches of the Grama Panchayats and Presidents of Panchayathi Samithis were elected directly by the electorate. It was also in his term that the age of voting was reduced from 21 to 18. Anjaiah received much appreciation for this bold step.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vaxxeoPUuqsC&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=anjaiah%20as%20union%20minister&source=bl&ots=GCW0YNdiGr&sig=SFG--IfmU3pQvQanbx7Wqc9fB30&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiohqOi2PHNAhVDGB4KHeCVDtQQ6AEIODAE#v=onepage&q=anjaiah%20as%20union%20minister&f=false|title=State Politics in India: Reflections on Andhra Pradesh|first=Agarala Easwara|last=Reddi|date=1 January 1994|publisher=M.D. Publications Pvt. Ltd.|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nT. Anjaiah offered help to Dr.[[Prathap C. Reddy]] to start a hospital in Andhra Pradesh. Anjaiah indeed lived up to his promise by offering 7 acres of land at the heart of the city at Sanjeevaih Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MxFMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT240&lpg=PT240&dq=tanguturi%20anjaiah&source=bl&ots=5tba2uTB-m&sig=PUrutNxT1HEh4EoZQPXDlY__Klw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQmcj_7_HNAhUFph4KHd5hDfQ4ChDoAQhYMA8#v=onepage&q=tanguturi%20anjaiah&f=false|title=Healer: Dr Prathap Chandra Reddy and the Transformation of India|first=Pranay|last=Gupte|date=15 December 2013|publisher=Penguin UK|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nT. Anjaiah's Chief Minister relief fund sponsored Hyderabad's first Kidney transplant surgery in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/34-years-after-citys-first-renal-transplant/article8605587.ece|title=34 years after city\u2019s first renal transplant|first=Rohit|last=Ps|date=16 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref> The idea of making the film on [[Tanguturi Prakasam]] came to [[Vijayachander]] on the motivation by T. Anjaiah in one of his speeches, that Government would provide financial assistance to such ventures. It was under the tenure of T. Anjaiah, Buddha Purnima Project Authority was conceptualized in 1991 including the decision to unveil a gigantic statue of the Buddha on the rock, amid the placid waters of the Hussain Sagar lake.\n\n== Honors==\n[[Lumbini Park]] in Hyderabad was renamed as T. Anjaiah Lumbini park on his memory in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/article3090281.ece|title=YSR to unveil Anjaiah's statue on August 16|author=|date=14 August 2006|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nChief Minister Y.S. Rajasekhara Reddy unveiled the statue of former Chief Minister late T. Anjaiah at Lumbini Park, opposite Secretariat in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/ysr-reiterates-promise-on-housing-for-the-poor/article3091748.ece|title=YSR reiterates promise on housing for the poor|author=|date=17 August 2006|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n==Incident with Rajiv Gandhi==\nIn 1982, [[Rajiv Gandhi]], then the [[All India Congress Committee|AICC]] general secretary, visited Andhra Pradesh on a \u2018private\u2019 visit. Anjaiah, who then was the Chief Minister arrived at the Begumpet airport amidst a crowd of about 200 waiting to welcome him, armed with garlands and with his entire cabinet in attendance. An angry Rajiv was disgusted by the pomp and pageantry and the euphoric, dancing crowd beating drums outside the airport. Multiple reports claim that Gandhi, in a moment of anger, publicly referred to Anjaiah as a 'buffoon' and that Anjaiah was in tears when the tirade ended. Back in Delhi, Rajiv was said to have convinced Indira Gandhi to sack Anjaiah. While giving up his post, Anjaiah was reported to have remarked that he came to power by the \u2018grace of Madam\u2019 and he was leaving under her orders, but he did not know why he had come or why he had to leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/indiascope/story/19820228-rajiv-gandhi-gives-andhra-cm-t.m.-anjiah-a-piece-of-his-mind-for-flouting-airport-rules-771544-2013-10-19#ssologin=1#source=magazine|title=Rajiv Gandhi gives Andhra CM T.M. Anjiah a piece of his mind for flouting airport rules|first=Amarnath|last=Menon|date=28 February 1982|publisher=[[India Today]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2008/may/30flip.htm|title=The arrogance of political dynasties|first=|last=|date=30 May 2008|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/rajiv-shadow-in-rahul-snub/cid/604622|title=Rajiv shadow in Rahul snub|first=Radhika|last=Ramaseshan|date=29 March 2008|publisher=[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe treatment meted out to Anjaiah was noted to be crucial in the Congress Party tasting its first-ever defeat in Andhra Pradesh in the 1983 Assembly elections. The [[Telugu Desam Party]] led by [[Nandamuri Taraka Rama Rao]] used the perceived insult as an affront to \"Telugu vari atmagauravam\" (Telugus' self-respect) to woo the voters and won the assembly elections with a thumping majority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/india-news/politics/all-you-need-to-know-about-pm-modis-reference-to-rajiv-gandhi-shouting-at-an-airport.html|title=All You Need To Know About PM Modi\u2019s Reference To Rajiv Gandhi \"Shouting\" At An Airport|first=Natasha|last=Patidar|date=15 February 2018|publisher=[[Republic TV]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/how-ntr-convinced-indira-gandhi-strong-states-did-not-mean-weak-centre-79068|title=How NTR convinced Indira Gandhi that strong states did not mean a weak Centre|first=Rasheed|last=Kidwai|date=5 April 2018|publisher=[[The News Minute]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/a-rajiv-gandhi-story-on-telugu-pride-in-pm-narendra-modis-parliament-offensive-1809724|title=A Rajiv Gandhi Story on \"Telugu Pride\" In PM Modi's Parliament Offensive|first=Uma|last=Sudhir|date=5 February 2018|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAnjaiah was married to [[T. Manemma]]. They have one son and four daughters. His family lived in Barkatpura Hyderabad until and after few years of his death.\n\nAnjaiah was in public life till his sudden death in 1986. After his death, his wife T. Manemma served as a [[Secunderabad]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] and as the [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] for [[Musheerabad]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Chief Ministers of Andhra Pradesh]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://164.100.47.132/LssNew/biodata_1_12/2968.htm Biodata of T. Anjaiah at Lok Sabha website]\n{{Chief Ministers of Andhra Pradesh}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anjaiah, Tanguturi}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Telugu politicians]]\n[[Category:8th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Telangana politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Secunderabad]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Tanguturi Anjaiah\n| image =Tanguturi Anjayya statue.jpg \n| caption =Statue of Tanguturi Anjayya\n| birth_date = 1919\n| birth_place = [[Hyderabad State]], [[India]]\n| residence = [[Bhanoor]], [[Hyderabad, Telangana|Hyderabad]], [[Telangana]], India\n| death_date = 1986 (aged 67 years)\n| death_place =\n| order        = 7th\n| office       = Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh\n| constituency =\n| term_start   = 11 October 1980\n| term_end     = 24 February 1982\n| predecessor  = [[Marri Chenna Reddy]]\n| successor    = [[Bhavanam Venkatarami Reddy]]\n| constituency_MP1 = [[Secunderabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Secunderabad]]\n| parliament1  = Indian\n| term_start1  = 31 December 1984\n| term_end1    = 27 November 1986\n| predecessor1 = [[P. Shiv Shankar]]\n| successor1   = [[T. Manemma]]\n| party =[[Congress (I)]]\n| religion = [[Hinduism]]\n| spouse = [[T. Manemma]]\n| children = 1 son and 4 daughters\n| website =\n| footnotes =|\n| year = |\n|image_upright=}}\n'''Tanguturi Anjaiah'''  (1919\u20131986) was the 7th [[Chief Minister]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]], India, from October 1980 to February 1982.\n\n==Early life==\nTanguturi Anjaiah, known as T. Anjaiah alias Ramakrishna Reddy Talla was born on August 16, 1919. His parents belonged to Bhanoor village in Medak district. It was alleged that Anjaiah belonged to a [[Backward Caste]] or a [[Dalit]] community and had changed his name to Ramakrishna Reddy and got into marital alliances with Reddys to garner the support of the politically powerful [[Reddy]] community for his Chief Ministerial tenure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/article3090281.ece|title=Can a BC hope to become first CM of T?|author=[[K Ramachandra Murthy]]|date=13 March 2014|publisher=[[The Hans India]]|accessdate=25 October 2019|via=The Hans India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/rajiv-shadow-in-rahul-snub/cid/604622|title=Rajiv shadow in Rahul snub|first=Radhika|last=Ramaseshan|date=29 March 2008|publisher=[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAnjaiah studied at Sultan Bazar high school. He couldn't pursue further education after matriculation due to financial difficulties so he started working at [[Hyderabad Allwyn]] for a daily wage of 6 anna (equal to 24 pice).\n\nAnjaiah faced many adversities in his early life which made him a fighter for the cause of social justice.\n\n==Career==\nT. Anjaiah rose from a being worker at [[Hyderabad Allwyn Limited]] in [[Hyderabad State|Hyderabad]] to become a trade union leader and later Union Labour Minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/article3090281.ece|title=YSR to unveil Anjaiah's statue on August 16|author=|date=14 August 2006|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nT. Anjaiah was nominated by the ruling party to replace [[Marri Chenna Reddy]] as Chief Minister on 11 October 1980. At the time of nomination, Anjaiah was the union minister of state for Labour. Anjaiah inducted all 15 dissident members of Chenna Reddy cabinet and formed the biggest state ministry the country had ever known.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/2004/03/26/stories/2004032604711300.htm|title=The Hindu : POLL-POURRI|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> He reduced it to 45 member on advice of center.\n\nAs the [[Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh]], he was known for his accommodating politics.\n\nThe two young uprising politicians at that time, Dr. [[Y. S. Rajasekhara Reddy]] and [[N. Chandrababu Naidu]], gained importance during Anjaiah's term as Chief Minister. A proposal to make [[N. T. Rama Rao|NTR]] a member of the Rajya Sabha did the rounds during this time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/52008486/Humanists-Chief-Ministers-I-Met|title=Humanists Chief Ministers I Met|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> Anjaiah was a mentor of [[P. Janardhan Reddy]].\n\nT. Anjaiah faced opponents including some of the ministers in his party after the ruling party lost Municipal elections in Visakhapatnam and Vijayawada. Asked by Mrs. Gandhi to step down on February 13, Anjiah tendered his resignation officially seven days later on February 20, 1982. Anjiah as a leader without followers could evoke unimaginable public sympathy. At his last public appearance as the chief minister, the day before he resigned Anjaiah was cheered by a 30,000-strong crowd. C. Jagannath Rao, who served in his cabinet as a home minister recalls him as, \"Whatever one may say against him, his remarkable simplicity endeared him to the people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/andhra-pradesh-cm-tanguturi-anjiah-unceremoniously-fired-by-congress-high-command/1/391472.html|title=Andhra Pradesh CM Tanguturi Anjiah unceremoniously fired by Congress high command|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Bhavanam Venkatarami Reddy]] replaced T. Anjaiah on February 24, 1982. [[Bhavanam Venkatarami Reddy]] himself was a dissident minister in the Marri Chenna Reddy ministry. T. Anjaiah was elected as Member of Parliament in 1984 from Secundrabad constituency.\n\n==Notable work ==\nT. Anjaiah's earliest act as Chief Minister was to conduct elections to the Panchayati Raj bodies and Municipalities. It was the first time the Sarpanches of the Grama Panchayats and Presidents of Panchayathi Samithis were elected directly by the electorate. It was also in his term that the age of voting was reduced from 21 to 18. Anjaiah received much appreciation for this bold step.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vaxxeoPUuqsC&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=anjaiah%20as%20union%20minister&source=bl&ots=GCW0YNdiGr&sig=SFG--IfmU3pQvQanbx7Wqc9fB30&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiohqOi2PHNAhVDGB4KHeCVDtQQ6AEIODAE#v=onepage&q=anjaiah%20as%20union%20minister&f=false|title=State Politics in India: Reflections on Andhra Pradesh|first=Agarala Easwara|last=Reddi|date=1 January 1994|publisher=M.D. Publications Pvt. Ltd.|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nT. Anjaiah offered help to Dr.[[Prathap C. Reddy]] to start a hospital in Andhra Pradesh. Anjaiah indeed lived up to his promise by offering 7 acres of land at the heart of the city at Sanjeevaih Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MxFMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT240&lpg=PT240&dq=tanguturi%20anjaiah&source=bl&ots=5tba2uTB-m&sig=PUrutNxT1HEh4EoZQPXDlY__Klw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQmcj_7_HNAhUFph4KHd5hDfQ4ChDoAQhYMA8#v=onepage&q=tanguturi%20anjaiah&f=false|title=Healer: Dr Prathap Chandra Reddy and the Transformation of India|first=Pranay|last=Gupte|date=15 December 2013|publisher=Penguin UK|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nT. Anjaiah's Chief Minister relief fund sponsored Hyderabad's first Kidney transplant surgery in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/34-years-after-citys-first-renal-transplant/article8605587.ece|title=34 years after city\u2019s first renal transplant|first=Rohit|last=Ps|date=16 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref> The idea of making the film on [[Tanguturi Prakasam]] came to [[Vijayachander]] on the motivation by T. Anjaiah in one of his speeches, that Government would provide financial assistance to such ventures. It was under the tenure of T. Anjaiah, Buddha Purnima Project Authority was conceptualized in 1991 including the decision to unveil a gigantic statue of the Buddha on the rock, amid the placid waters of the Hussain Sagar lake.\n\n== Honors==\n[[Lumbini Park]] in Hyderabad was renamed as T. Anjaiah Lumbini park on his memory in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/article3090281.ece|title=YSR to unveil Anjaiah's statue on August 16|author=|date=14 August 2006|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nChief Minister Y.S. Rajasekhara Reddy unveiled the statue of former Chief Minister late T. Anjaiah at Lumbini Park, opposite Secretariat in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/ysr-reiterates-promise-on-housing-for-the-poor/article3091748.ece|title=YSR reiterates promise on housing for the poor|author=|date=17 August 2006|publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n==Incident with Rajiv Gandhi==\nIn 1982, [[Rajiv Gandhi]], then the [[All India Congress Committee|AICC]] general secretary, visited Andhra Pradesh on a \u2018private\u2019 visit. Anjaiah, who then was the Chief Minister arrived at the Begumpet airport amidst a crowd of about 200 waiting to welcome him, armed with garlands and with his entire cabinet in attendance. An angry Rajiv was disgusted by the pomp and pageantry and the euphoric, dancing crowd beating drums outside the airport. Multiple reports claim that Gandhi, in a moment of anger, publicly referred to Anjaiah as a 'buffoon' and that Anjaiah was in tears when the tirade ended. Back in Delhi, Rajiv was said to have convinced Indira Gandhi to sack Anjaiah. While giving up his post, Anjaiah was reported to have remarked that he came to power by the \u2018grace of Madam\u2019 and he was leaving under her orders, but he did not know why he had come or why he had to leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/indiascope/story/19820228-rajiv-gandhi-gives-andhra-cm-t.m.-anjiah-a-piece-of-his-mind-for-flouting-airport-rules-771544-2013-10-19#ssologin=1#source=magazine|title=Rajiv Gandhi gives Andhra CM T.M. Anjiah a piece of his mind for flouting airport rules|first=Amarnath|last=Menon|date=28 February 1982|publisher=[[India Today]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/news/2008/may/30flip.htm|title=The arrogance of political dynasties|first=|last=|date=30 May 2008|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/rajiv-shadow-in-rahul-snub/cid/604622|title=Rajiv shadow in Rahul snub|first=Radhika|last=Ramaseshan|date=29 March 2008|publisher=[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe treatment meted out to Anjaiah was noted to be crucial in the Congress Party tasting its first-ever defeat in Andhra Pradesh in the 1983 Assembly elections. The [[Telugu Desam Party]] led by [[Nandamuri Taraka Rama Rao]] used the perceived insult as an affront to \"Telugu vari atmagauravam\" (Telugus' self-respect) to woo the voters and won the assembly elections with a thumping majority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/india-news/politics/all-you-need-to-know-about-pm-modis-reference-to-rajiv-gandhi-shouting-at-an-airport.html|title=All You Need To Know About PM Modi\u2019s Reference To Rajiv Gandhi \"Shouting\" At An Airport|first=Natasha|last=Patidar|date=15 February 2018|publisher=[[Republic TV]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/how-ntr-convinced-indira-gandhi-strong-states-did-not-mean-weak-centre-79068|title=How NTR convinced Indira Gandhi that strong states did not mean a weak Centre|first=Rasheed|last=Kidwai|date=5 April 2018|publisher=[[The News Minute]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/a-rajiv-gandhi-story-on-telugu-pride-in-pm-narendra-modis-parliament-offensive-1809724|title=A Rajiv Gandhi Story on \"Telugu Pride\" In PM Modi's Parliament Offensive|first=Uma|last=Sudhir|date=5 February 2018|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAnjaiah was married to [[T. Manemma]]. They have one son and four daughters. His family lived in Barkatpura Hyderabad until and after few years of his death.\n\nAnjaiah was in public life till his sudden death in 1986. After his death, his wife T. Manemma served as a [[Secunderabad]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] and as the [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] for [[Musheerabad]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Chief Ministers of Andhra Pradesh]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://164.100.47.132/LssNew/biodata_1_12/2968.htm Biodata of T. Anjaiah at Lok Sabha website]\n{{Chief Ministers of Andhra Pradesh}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anjaiah, Tanguturi}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Telugu politicians]]\n[[Category:8th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Telangana politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Secunderabad]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Sainredd", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tanguturi_Anjaiah"}
{"title_page": "Pinjra Tod", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2017}}\n\n'''Pinjra Tod''' (''Break the Cage'') is a collective of women students and alumni of colleges from across [[Delhi]], India, that seeks to make regulations for hostel and paying guest (PG) accommodation less  restrictive for women students. They aim to counter a perceived official narrative that women need to be protected. Challenging what they consider to be the CCTV-driven police-security complex, Pinjra Tod demands that concepts of safety and security not be used to silence women's right to mobility and liberation. \n\nThe main specific goals of Pinjra Tod are to end the imposition of curfews on women, to provide affordable accommodation for women, to regularise the situation for paying guests, and to obtain the formation of elected Internal Complaint Committees for prevention, prohibition and redress of sexual harassment in universities.\n\n== Background ==\n\nIn 2015, when Delhi's universities reopened after the summer break, [[Jamia Millia Islamia]] issued a notice stating that the female students of the college could no longer request permission to stay out later than 8 pm. The Delhi Commission for Women (DCW) challenged this, asking why the college administration thought it necessary to impose such a restriction.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nA group of women students identified the reaction of DCW as an opening to make interventions at other universities in Delhi, rather than just Jamia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youthkiawaaz.com/2015/10/pinjra-tod-jan-sunwai-interview/|title=An Exclusive Chat With Pinjra Tod Organisers On The Campaign, Its Vision, And Future|date=2015-10-14|work=Youth Ki Awaaz|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en-US}}</ref> They decided to circulate a petition<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/pinjra-tod-womens-body-accepts-groups-demands/|title=Sign the Petition|website=Change.org|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref> to extend the discourse sparked by the Jamia incident, questioning the exclusive and exclusionary treatment that they believe applies in university spaces. Pinjra Tod mobilised people around several issues faced by female residents of hostels and PGs such as curfews, policies that apply to only women,<ref name=\"Azad\">{{Cite web|url=http://feminisminindia.com/2015/09/30/pinjra-tod-stop-caging-women-behind-college-hostel-bars/|title=Pinjra Tod: Stop Caging Women Behind College Hostel Bars|last=Azad|first=Nikita|date=2015-09-30|website=Feminism in India|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> moral policing,<ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/education/news/Pinjra-Tod-campaigners-threatened-to-be-beaten-up-for-pasting-posters/articleshow/49052268.cms|title=Pinjra Tod campaigners threatened to be \"beaten up\" for pasting posters - Times of India|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> higher prices for women's hostels,<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.in\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2016/10/04/why-these-women-from-a-south-delhi-college-took-out-a-march-to-r/|title=These Women From A South Delhi College Took Out A March To Reclaim The Streets|website=Huffington Post India|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/pinjra-tod-stages-protest-against-high-university-hostel-fee/article19556804.ece|title=Pinjra Tod stages protest against high university hostel fee|last=Ara|first=Ismat|date=2017-08-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2017-09-11|last2=Ara|first2=Ismat|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> among others. It is also focused on ensuring that universities establish a sexual harassment committee, as mandated by [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grant Commission]] (UGC) guidelines in 2006.<ref name=\"dnaindia.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report-pinjra-tod-wave-gets-hostels-to-extend-curfew-2279112|title=Pinjra Tod wave gets hostels to extend curfew {{!}} Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=2016-12-03|newspaper=dna|access-date=2017-02-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSince then, the movement has seen participation from students of several colleges, especially from [[University of Delhi|Delhi University]], such as [[Jamia Millia Islamia|Jamia Milia Islamia]], Miranda House, [[Ambedkar University Delhi]], Hindu College, [[Lady Shri Ram College for Women|Lady Shriram College for Women]], St. Stephen's College,{{cn|date=March 2020}} and Delhi Technical University.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dtu-changes-curfew-timings-for-girls-brings-it-par-with-boys/1/1024479.html|title=DTU changes curfew timings for girls, brings it par with boys|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> The movement has garnered momentum across the country,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/z6E69WRoNJAyUuGU5yYwXO/How-Pinjra-Tod-spread-its-wings.html|title=How 'Pinjra Tod' spread its wings|last=Borpujari|first=Priyanka|date=2016-12-30|work=livemint.com/|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> with students from several colleges, such as [[National Institute of Technology Calicut|NIT Calicut]], [[Indian Institute of Technology Roorkee|IIT-Roorkee]], [[Punjabi University]], RMNLU Lucknow,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barandbench.com/pinjratod-movement-sees-a-victory-of-sorts-at-rmlnlu-after-change-in-hostel-timings/|title=#PinjraTod movement sees a victory (of sorts) at RMLNLU after change in hostel timings - Bar & Bench|last=Bench|first=Bar &|date=2015-11-28|work=Bar & Bench|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref> using the Pinjra Tod to challenge patriarchal policies women face in their campuses.<ref name=\"dnaindia.com\"/>\n\n== Activities ==\nThe petition organised by Pinjra Tod was submitted to the DCW on 10 October 2015<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/indian-women-push-back-against-campus-curfews/2015/10/21/6b739680-727e-11e5-ba14-318f8e87a2fc_story.html|title=Indian women push back against campus curfews|last=Lakshmi|first=Rama|date=2015-10-22|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> and was preceded on 8 October by a protest march in the North Campus of Delhi University to symbolically reclaim the night.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news18.com/news/india/pinjra-tod-fighting-against-discriminatory-directives-of-delhi-colleges-1121179.html|title='Pinjra Tod' fighting against discriminatory directives of Delhi colleges|work=News18|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\nReacting to a claim by Smriti Irani, the Minister of Human Resource Development who had said \"women in India are not told what to wear, whom to meet and where to go\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Women-in-India-free-says-Smriti-Irani-booed/articleshow/49867251.cms|title=Women in India free, says Smriti Irani; booed - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> on 24 October 2015, Pinjra Tod called for a protest at her ministry offices. Titled \"FYI Smriti Irani\", it saw the minister presented with copies of rule-books from various hostels.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 16 December 2015, Pinjra Tod organised a multi-city protest called, 'Bus Teri Meri, Chal Saheli,'<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/they-sang-they-laughed-they-conquered-how-a-group-of-angry-women-reclaimed-their-space-in-the-society-pinjra-tod-patriarcy-hostel-rules-deadlines-delhi-pune-chandigarh-patiala/1/549417.html|title=A simultaneous protest in seven cities against hostel rules imposed after December 16, was highly inspiring|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> three years post [[2012 Delhi gang rape]]. The idea was to use public transport at night and reconfigure public spaces which are always already assumed to be posing 'danger' to women. The initiate challenged the patriarchal ideology which imagines women only in terms of violence in the discourse of violation of security.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} Parallel demonstrations took place in Allahabad, Kolkata, Pune, Bangalore, Delhi, Darjeeling, Chandigarh and Patiala.{{cn|date=March 2020}} Similar protests were repeated in December 2016, where women were seen in the heart of the capital, [[Connaught Place, New Delhi]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn February 2016, the group released a statement after charges of sedition were slapped against [[JNU sedition row|JNU students.]] The statement was called, 'No Nation for Women,' and it addressed the question of nationalism\u2014unpacking the 'anti-national/national' binary and how the very idea of nationalism is built on layers of exclusion of minorities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eyeartcollective.com/no-nation-for-women-pinjra-tod/|title=No Nation For Women : Pinjra Tod {{!}} EYEZINE|date=2016-02-27|work=EYEZINE|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-GB}}</ref> They group answered the calls to 'Bharat Maata Ki Jai,' with 'Bharat Ki Mata Nahi Banenge,'<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forwardpress.in/2017/08/bharat-mata-and-her-unruly-daughters/|title=Bharat Mata and her unruly daughters|date=2017-08-25|work=Forward Press|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref> with the end to prove how hyper masculinity often masquerades as patriotism.\n\nOn 2 May 2016, the UGC published in ''[[The Gazette of India]]'', a letter regarding Prevention, Prohibition, and Redressal of Sexual Harassment of Women Employees and Students in Higher Educational Institutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ugc.ac.in/ugc_notices.aspx?id=1433|title=UGC letter reg.:Prevention,prohibition and redressal of sexual harassment of women employees and students in higher educational institutions.(published in the Gazette of India dated 2nd, May, 2016)|website=ugc.ac.in|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> On 7 May 2016, the DCW issued notices to 23 universities, acting on Pinjra Tod's report.<ref name=\"The Quint\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thequint.com/voices/women/pinjra-tod-happy-to-have-dcw-act-but-fight-still-far-from-over|title=Pinjra Tod: Happy to Have DCW Act, but Fight Still Far From Over|work=The Quint|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en}}</ref> Acting on the compaint submitted to the DCW by Pinjra Tod in November 2015, regarding discriminatory rules in several women's hostels in Delhi. DCW later, also issued notices to seven colleges asking for an explanation regarding why hostel curfew timings differ for men and women.<ref name=\"dnaindia.com\"/><ref name=\"The Quint\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theladiesfinger.com/pinjra-tod-interview/|title=Pinjra Tod Breaks a Lock: Delhi Commission for Women Issues Notice to Universities - The Ladies FingerThe Ladies Finger|website=theladiesfinger.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Pinjra Tod undertook a \u2018night march\u2019 in North Campus on Monday against the Delhi University Students\u2019 Union (DUSU) elections, protesting against the violent nature of electoral politics on campus.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/night-march-against-dusu-elections/article29386861.ece</ref>\n\n== Public art  ==\nIn September 2015, within weeks of the movement's inception, there was wall art and graffiti painted across North Campus, Delhi University, featuring Pinjra Tod's name and pictures of birds escaping from cages. One of the founders of Pinjra Tod, which first became a public entity via a Facebook page, said that the creators of the work were unknown.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://scroll.in/article/755709/heres-why-graffiti-on-delhi-university-walls-is-exhorting-women-hostellers-to-break-the-locks|title=Here's why graffiti on Delhi University walls is exhorting women hostellers to 'break the locks'|last=Jain|first=Mayank|work=Scroll.in|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 September 2015, two Pinjra Tod activists claimed to have received a phone call from a man who said he was a student of Satyawati College and a member of [[Akhil Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad]] (ABVP). He had got their phone number from posters they had pasted on top of others at the Wall of Democracy. Objecting to the way in which their actions had obscured other posters, the man allegedly threatened to beat up the women activists if they repeated their actions. ABVP said that the caller did not speak on behalf of the organisation and that they had no objection to Pinjra Tod or the posters put up by it. Pinjra Tod filed a [[First Information Report]] and produced a new poster saying \"You can't lock the walls\".<ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/delhi-charges-fly-thick-and-fast-as-pinjra-tod-campaign-on-campus-takes-an-ugly-turn/|title=Delhi: Charges fly thick and fast as Pinjra Tod campaign on campus takes an ugly turn|date=2015-09-23|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/pinjra-tod-members-file-fir/article7678863.ece|title=Pinjra Tod members file FIR|last=Sebastian|first=Kritika Sharma|date=2015-09-23|work=The Hindu|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nA year later, Pinjra Tod campaigners organised a \"graffiti drive\" at Ambedkar University that protested a wide range of social matters, not all related to women and/or their hostels. Their work was then challenged with anti-feminist graffiti, leading them to respond with further examples.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Ambedkar-University-girls-give-fitting-reply-to-anti-feminist-comments-via-graffiti/articleshow/54736605.cms|title=Ambedkar University girls give fitting reply to anti-feminist comments via graffiti - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 September 2016, Pinjra Tod had organised a night march and vigil in North Campus to end sexist diktats and discriminatory hostel rules, which was allegedly disrupted by ABVP activists.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Pinjra-Tod-rails-against-harassment-by-ABVP/articleshow/54966249.cms|title=Pinjra Tod rails against 'harassment' by ABVP - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Pinjra Tod later released a video to substantiate its claim.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nFollowing the disqualification (later overturned) of Lakshya, the drama society of Kamla Nehru College, for using words like ''bra'' and ''panty'' in their play at a theatre festival organised by [[Sahitya Kala Parishad]] on 13 February 2017, members of Pinjra Tod protested by performing a piece titled \"An Ode to Bra, Panty and the Sahitya Kala Academy\". They also hung bras on the outer wall of the [[Shriram Bharatiya Kala Kendra|Shri Ram Centre for Performing Arts]], where the performance took place, to protest the stigmatisation of women's undergarments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi/kamla-nehru-college-students-hang-bras-on-wall-to-protest-get-disqualification-rolled-back/story-1VtDPKNcLwL8T3ifkPy8JK.html|title=Students hang bras on wall to protest, get disqualification rolled back|date=2017-02-01|newspaper=http://www.hindustantimes.com/|access-date=2017-02-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{facebook|pinjratod}}\n{{Campus violence in India}}\n[[Category:Social movements in India]]\n[[Category:Activism in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2017}}\n\n'''Pinjra Tod''' (''Break the Cage'') is a collective of women students and alumni of colleges from across [[Delhi]], India, that seeks to make regulations for hostel and paying guest (PG) accommodation less  restrictive for women students. They aim to counter a perceived official narrative that women need to be protected. Challenging what they consider to be the CCTV-driven police-security complex, Pinjra Tod demands that concepts of safety and security not be used to silence women's right to mobility and liberation. \n\nThe main specific goals of Pinjra Tod are to end the imposition of curfews on women, to provide affordable accommodation for women, to regularise the situation for paying guests, and to obtain the formation of elected Internal Complaint Committees for prevention, prohibition and redress of sexual harassment in universities.\n\nIt has been claimed that Pinjra Tod reflects nepotistic tendencies by reiterating the views and perceptions of the elite [[savarna]] group within Indian society<ref>https://livewire.thewire.in/gender-and-sexuality/pinjra-tod-your-time-is-up-why-bahujan-tribal-and-muslim-women-are-quitting-the-collective/</ref> and that it has failed to achieve the reforms it seeks. It has been widely accused of hypocrisy and subtle patriarchy.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Background ==\n\nIn 2015, when Delhi's universities reopened after the summer break, [[Jamia Millia Islamia]] issued a notice stating that the female students of the college could no longer request permission to stay out later than 8 pm. The Delhi Commission for Women (DCW) challenged this, asking why the college administration thought it necessary to impose such a restriction.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nA group of women students identified the reaction of DCW as an opening to make interventions at other universities in Delhi, rather than just Jamia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youthkiawaaz.com/2015/10/pinjra-tod-jan-sunwai-interview/|title=An Exclusive Chat With Pinjra Tod Organisers On The Campaign, Its Vision, And Future|date=2015-10-14|work=Youth Ki Awaaz|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en-US}}</ref> They decided to circulate a petition<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/pinjra-tod-womens-body-accepts-groups-demands/|title=Sign the Petition|website=Change.org|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref> to extend the discourse sparked by the Jamia incident, questioning the exclusive and exclusionary treatment that they believe applies in university spaces. Pinjra Tod mobilised people around several issues faced by female residents of hostels and PGs such as curfews, policies that apply to only women,<ref name=\"Azad\">{{Cite web|url=http://feminisminindia.com/2015/09/30/pinjra-tod-stop-caging-women-behind-college-hostel-bars/|title=Pinjra Tod: Stop Caging Women Behind College Hostel Bars|last=Azad|first=Nikita|date=2015-09-30|website=Feminism in India|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> moral policing,<ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/education/news/Pinjra-Tod-campaigners-threatened-to-be-beaten-up-for-pasting-posters/articleshow/49052268.cms|title=Pinjra Tod campaigners threatened to be \"beaten up\" for pasting posters - Times of India|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> higher prices for women's hostels,<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.in\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2016/10/04/why-these-women-from-a-south-delhi-college-took-out-a-march-to-r/|title=These Women From A South Delhi College Took Out A March To Reclaim The Streets|website=Huffington Post India|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/pinjra-tod-stages-protest-against-high-university-hostel-fee/article19556804.ece|title=Pinjra Tod stages protest against high university hostel fee|last=Ara|first=Ismat|date=2017-08-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2017-09-11|last2=Ara|first2=Ismat|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> among others. It is also focused on ensuring that universities establish a sexual harassment committee, as mandated by [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grant Commission]] (UGC) guidelines in 2006.<ref name=\"dnaindia.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report-pinjra-tod-wave-gets-hostels-to-extend-curfew-2279112|title=Pinjra Tod wave gets hostels to extend curfew {{!}} Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=2016-12-03|newspaper=dna|access-date=2017-02-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSince then, the movement has seen participation from students of several colleges, especially from [[University of Delhi|Delhi University]], such as [[Jamia Millia Islamia|Jamia Milia Islamia]], Miranda House, [[Ambedkar University Delhi]], Hindu College, [[Lady Shri Ram College for Women|Lady Shriram College for Women]], St. Stephen's College,{{cn|date=March 2020}} and Delhi Technical University.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dtu-changes-curfew-timings-for-girls-brings-it-par-with-boys/1/1024479.html|title=DTU changes curfew timings for girls, brings it par with boys|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> The movement has garnered momentum across the country,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/z6E69WRoNJAyUuGU5yYwXO/How-Pinjra-Tod-spread-its-wings.html|title=How 'Pinjra Tod' spread its wings|last=Borpujari|first=Priyanka|date=2016-12-30|work=livemint.com/|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> with students from several colleges, such as [[National Institute of Technology Calicut|NIT Calicut]], [[Indian Institute of Technology Roorkee|IIT-Roorkee]], [[Punjabi University]], RMNLU Lucknow,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barandbench.com/pinjratod-movement-sees-a-victory-of-sorts-at-rmlnlu-after-change-in-hostel-timings/|title=#PinjraTod movement sees a victory (of sorts) at RMLNLU after change in hostel timings - Bar & Bench|last=Bench|first=Bar &|date=2015-11-28|work=Bar & Bench|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref> using the Pinjra Tod to challenge patriarchal policies women face in their campuses.<ref name=\"dnaindia.com\"/>\n\n== Activities ==\nThe petition organised by Pinjra Tod was submitted to the DCW on 10 October 2015<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/indian-women-push-back-against-campus-curfews/2015/10/21/6b739680-727e-11e5-ba14-318f8e87a2fc_story.html|title=Indian women push back against campus curfews|last=Lakshmi|first=Rama|date=2015-10-22|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> and was preceded on 8 October by a protest march in the North Campus of Delhi University to symbolically reclaim the night.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news18.com/news/india/pinjra-tod-fighting-against-discriminatory-directives-of-delhi-colleges-1121179.html|title='Pinjra Tod' fighting against discriminatory directives of Delhi colleges|work=News18|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\nReacting to a claim by Smriti Irani, the Minister of Human Resource Development who had said \"women in India are not told what to wear, whom to meet and where to go\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Women-in-India-free-says-Smriti-Irani-booed/articleshow/49867251.cms|title=Women in India free, says Smriti Irani; booed - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> on 24 October 2015, Pinjra Tod called for a protest at her ministry offices. Titled \"FYI Smriti Irani\", it saw the minister presented with copies of rule-books from various hostels.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 16 December 2015, Pinjra Tod organised a multi-city protest called, 'Bus Teri Meri, Chal Saheli,'<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/they-sang-they-laughed-they-conquered-how-a-group-of-angry-women-reclaimed-their-space-in-the-society-pinjra-tod-patriarcy-hostel-rules-deadlines-delhi-pune-chandigarh-patiala/1/549417.html|title=A simultaneous protest in seven cities against hostel rules imposed after December 16, was highly inspiring|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> three years post [[2012 Delhi gang rape]]. The idea was to use public transport at night and reconfigure public spaces which are always already assumed to be posing 'danger' to women. The initiate challenged the patriarchal ideology which imagines women only in terms of violence in the discourse of violation of security.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} Parallel demonstrations took place in Allahabad, Kolkata, Pune, Bangalore, Delhi, Darjeeling, Chandigarh and Patiala.{{cn|date=March 2020}} Similar protests were repeated in December 2016, where women were seen in the heart of the capital, [[Connaught Place, New Delhi]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn February 2016, the group released a statement after charges of sedition were slapped against [[JNU sedition row|JNU students.]] The statement was called, 'No Nation for Women,' and it addressed the question of nationalism\u2014unpacking the 'anti-national/national' binary and how the very idea of nationalism is built on layers of exclusion of minorities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eyeartcollective.com/no-nation-for-women-pinjra-tod/|title=No Nation For Women : Pinjra Tod {{!}} EYEZINE|date=2016-02-27|work=EYEZINE|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-GB}}</ref> They group answered the calls to 'Bharat Maata Ki Jai,' with 'Bharat Ki Mata Nahi Banenge,'<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forwardpress.in/2017/08/bharat-mata-and-her-unruly-daughters/|title=Bharat Mata and her unruly daughters|date=2017-08-25|work=Forward Press|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref> with the end to prove how hyper masculinity often masquerades as patriotism.\n\nOn 2 May 2016, the UGC published in ''[[The Gazette of India]]'', a letter regarding Prevention, Prohibition, and Redressal of Sexual Harassment of Women Employees and Students in Higher Educational Institutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ugc.ac.in/ugc_notices.aspx?id=1433|title=UGC letter reg.:Prevention,prohibition and redressal of sexual harassment of women employees and students in higher educational institutions.(published in the Gazette of India dated 2nd, May, 2016)|website=ugc.ac.in|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> On 7 May 2016, the DCW issued notices to 23 universities, acting on Pinjra Tod's report.<ref name=\"The Quint\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thequint.com/voices/women/pinjra-tod-happy-to-have-dcw-act-but-fight-still-far-from-over|title=Pinjra Tod: Happy to Have DCW Act, but Fight Still Far From Over|work=The Quint|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en}}</ref> Acting on the compaint submitted to the DCW by Pinjra Tod in November 2015, regarding discriminatory rules in several women's hostels in Delhi. DCW later, also issued notices to seven colleges asking for an explanation regarding why hostel curfew timings differ for men and women.<ref name=\"dnaindia.com\"/><ref name=\"The Quint\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theladiesfinger.com/pinjra-tod-interview/|title=Pinjra Tod Breaks a Lock: Delhi Commission for Women Issues Notice to Universities - The Ladies FingerThe Ladies Finger|website=theladiesfinger.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Pinjra Tod undertook a \u2018night march\u2019 in North Campus on Monday against the Delhi University Students\u2019 Union (DUSU) elections, protesting against the violent nature of electoral politics on campus.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/night-march-against-dusu-elections/article29386861.ece</ref>\n\n== Public art  ==\nIn September 2015, within weeks of the movement's inception, there was wall art and graffiti painted across North Campus, Delhi University, featuring Pinjra Tod's name and pictures of birds escaping from cages. One of the founders of Pinjra Tod, which first became a public entity via a Facebook page, said that the creators of the work were unknown.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://scroll.in/article/755709/heres-why-graffiti-on-delhi-university-walls-is-exhorting-women-hostellers-to-break-the-locks|title=Here's why graffiti on Delhi University walls is exhorting women hostellers to 'break the locks'|last=Jain|first=Mayank|work=Scroll.in|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 September 2015, two Pinjra Tod activists claimed to have received a phone call from a man who said he was a student of Satyawati College and a member of [[Akhil Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad]] (ABVP). He had got their phone number from posters they had pasted on top of others at the Wall of Democracy. Objecting to the way in which their actions had obscured other posters, the man allegedly threatened to beat up the women activists if they repeated their actions. ABVP said that the caller did not speak on behalf of the organisation and that they had no objection to Pinjra Tod or the posters put up by it. Pinjra Tod filed a [[First Information Report]] and produced a new poster saying \"You can't lock the walls\".<ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/delhi-charges-fly-thick-and-fast-as-pinjra-tod-campaign-on-campus-takes-an-ugly-turn/|title=Delhi: Charges fly thick and fast as Pinjra Tod campaign on campus takes an ugly turn|date=2015-09-23|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/pinjra-tod-members-file-fir/article7678863.ece|title=Pinjra Tod members file FIR|last=Sebastian|first=Kritika Sharma|date=2015-09-23|work=The Hindu|access-date=2017-09-12|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nA year later, Pinjra Tod campaigners organised a \"graffiti drive\" at Ambedkar University that protested a wide range of social matters, not all related to women and/or their hostels. Their work was then challenged with anti-feminist graffiti, leading them to respond with further examples.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Ambedkar-University-girls-give-fitting-reply-to-anti-feminist-comments-via-graffiti/articleshow/54736605.cms|title=Ambedkar University girls give fitting reply to anti-feminist comments via graffiti - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 September 2016, Pinjra Tod had organised a night march and vigil in North Campus to end sexist diktats and discriminatory hostel rules, which was allegedly disrupted by ABVP activists.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Pinjra-Tod-rails-against-harassment-by-ABVP/articleshow/54966249.cms|title=Pinjra Tod rails against 'harassment' by ABVP - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> Pinjra Tod later released a video to substantiate its claim.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nFollowing the disqualification (later overturned) of Lakshya, the drama society of Kamla Nehru College, for using words like ''bra'' and ''panty'' in their play at a theatre festival organised by [[Sahitya Kala Parishad]] on 13 February 2017, members of Pinjra Tod protested by performing a piece titled \"An Ode to Bra, Panty and the Sahitya Kala Academy\". They also hung bras on the outer wall of the [[Shriram Bharatiya Kala Kendra|Shri Ram Centre for Performing Arts]], where the performance took place, to protest the stigmatisation of women's undergarments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi/kamla-nehru-college-students-hang-bras-on-wall-to-protest-get-disqualification-rolled-back/story-1VtDPKNcLwL8T3ifkPy8JK.html|title=Students hang bras on wall to protest, get disqualification rolled back|date=2017-02-01|newspaper=http://www.hindustantimes.com/|access-date=2017-02-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Internal dissent==\nOn 20 February 2019, a group of women issued a statement announcing that they were leaving the movement because it was not inclusive or properly representative. Claiming \"Pinjra Tod is an organisation of Savarna Hindu women and like all other Savarna organisations it has failed women from marginalised race, castes and religion\", they argued that the emotional and physical work of Muslim women and those from the [[Scheduled Castes]], [[Scheduled Tribes]] and [[Other Backwards Class]]es had been exploited by Pinjra Tod and that the movement should be addressing wider issues of social abuse and harassment rather than concentrating on those related to gender. Referencing women's voices emboldened by the [[#MeToo movement]], the leavers said \"Thus, to Savarna feminists and Savarna women's organisations, we are no longer going to be fascinated by your sisterhood circles and tokenism inclusivity. Your Time is Up too.\" <ref>https://livewire.thewire.in/gender-and-sexuality/pinjra-tod-your-time-is-up-why-bahujan-tribal-and-muslim-women-are-quitting-the-collective/</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gawali|first=Sandhya|date=October 2019|title=Unpacking sexual harassment of women in the context of the #MeToo and the Pinjra Tod campaigns: feminist understandings|journal=Jindal Global Law Review|volume=10|issue=2|pages=287\u2013302|doi=10.1007/s41020-019-00108-y|issn=0975-2498}}</ref> A few days later, Pinjra Tod issued a response countering the charges raised.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{facebook|pinjratod}}\n{{Campus violence in India}}\n[[Category:Social movements in India]]\n[[Category:Activism in India]]\n", "name_user": "Madeeha22", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Again, it's just a set of allegations, it's a tit for that tat story. Wikipedia is not the platform for allegations and counter allegations.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinjra_Tod"}
{"title_page": "History of the Laz people", "text_new": "{{Laz people}}\nThe '''Laz people''' or '''Lazi''' ({{lang-ka|\u10da\u10d0\u10d6\u10d8}}, {{lang|ka-Latn|lazi}}; or {{lang|ka|\u10ed\u10d0\u10dc\u10d8}}, {{lang|ka-Latn|ch'ani}}; {{lang-tr|Laz}}) are an indigenous [[Kartvelian languages|Kartvelian]]-speaking [[ethnic group]]<ref name=\"ethno\">{{cite book|title=An Ethnohistorical Dictionary of the Russian and Soviet Empires|author=James S. Olson|publisher=Greenwood|year=1994|editors=Lee Brigance Pappas, Nicholas Charles Pappas|page=436|author-link=James S. Olson}}</ref> inhabiting [[Lazistan]], which today encompasses parts of [[Black Sea]] coastal regions of [[Black Sea Region|Turkey]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref>1 Minorsky, V. \"Laz.\" Encyclopaedia of Islam, Second Edition. Edited by: P. Bearman , Th. Bianquis , C.E . Bosworth , E. van Donzel and W.P. Heinrichs. Brill, 2010.</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Antiquity ===\n[[File:M\u00d6_6._y\u00fczy\u0131la_ait_g\u00fcm\u00fc\u015f_Kolkhis_sikkesi.jpg|left|thumb|[[Colchis|Colchian]] silver coin, 6th century BC]]\nIn the thirteenth century [[Common Era|BC]], the Kingdom of [[Colchis]] was formed as a result of the increasing consolidation of the tribes inhabiting the region, which covered modern western Georgia and [[Turkey]]'s north-eastern provinces of [[Trabzon Province|Trabzon]], [[Rize Province|Rize]] and [[Artvin Province|Artvin]].<ref name=\"Andrew Andersen p. 91\">Andrew Andersen, History of Ancient Caucasus, p.&nbsp;91</ref> Colchis was an important region in Black Sea trade \u2013 rich with gold, wax, hemp, and honey. In the eighth century, several Greek [[Colonies in antiquity|trading colonies]] were established along the shores of the Black Sea, one of them being Trebizond ({{lang-el|\u03a4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c0\u03b5\u03b6\u03bf\u1fe6\u03c2|Trapezous}}) founded by [[Milesians (Greek)|Milesian]] traders from [[Sinop, Turkey|Sinope]] in 756 BC. Trebizond's trade partners included the Proto-Laz tribes of [[Mossynoeci]].\n[[File:Ethnic_Caucasia-en.png|alt=|thumb|Ethnic map of the [[Caucasus]] in the 5th and 4th centuries BC]]\nBy the sixth century BC, the tribes living in the southern Colchis ([[Macrones]], [[Mossynoeci]], [[Marres]] etc.) were incorporated into the [[Nineteenth Satrapy|nineteenth satrapy]] of [[Achaemenid Empire|Persia]]. The Achaemenid Empire was defeated by [[Alexander the Great]], however following the Alexander's death a number of separate kingdoms were established in [[Anatolia]], including [[Kingdom of Pontus|Pontus]], in the corner of the southern Black Sea, ruled by the Persian nobleman [[Mithridates I of Pontus|Mithridates I]]. Culturally, the kingdom was [[Hellenization|Hellenized]],<ref>Children of Achilles: The Greeks in Asia Minor Since the Days of Troy, by John Freely, p. 69\u201370</ref> with Greek as the official language.<ref>The Foreign Policy of Mithridates VI Eupator, King of Pontus, by B.{{nbsp}}C. McGing, p. 11</ref> [[Mithridates VI of Pontus|Mithridates VI]] conquered the Colchis, and gave it to his son [[Mithridates of Colchis]].\n\nAs a result of the brilliant [[Mithridatic Wars|Roman campaigns]] between 88-63 BC, led by the generals [[Pompey]] and [[Lucullus]], the kingdom of Pontus was completely destroyed by the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] and all its territory, including Colchis, was incorporated into the Roman Empire. The former southern provinces of Colchis were reorganized into the [[Roman province]] of [[Pontus (region)|Pontus Polemoniacus]], while the northern Cholchis became the Roman province of [[Georgia in the Roman era|Lazicum]]. Roman control remained likewise only nominal over the tribes of the interior.<ref name=\"Talbert1226\">{{harvnb|Talbert|2000|p=1226}}.</ref>\n\nThe first-century historians [[Memnon of Heraclea|Memnon]] and [[Strabo]] remark in passing that the people formerly called Macrones bore in his day the name of [[Sanni]], a claim supported also by [[Stephanus of Byzantium]]. The second-century historian [[Arrian]] notes that [[Zans|Tzanni]], same as the Sanni<ref>[[Procopius]], ''History of the Wars'', I-II [21-25]</ref> are neighbours of the Colchians, while the latter were now referred to as the Lazi. By the mid-third century, the Lazi tribe came to dominate most of Colchis, establishing the [[Lazica|kingdom of Lazica]].\n\n=== Middle Ages ===\n[[File:Lazica_in_Late_Antiquity.svg|left|thumb|The kingdom of Lazica in late antiquity]]\nThe warlike tribes of the Chaldia, called Tzanni, the ancestors of modern Laz people lived in ''Tzanica'', the area located between the Byzantine and the Lazica. It included several settlements named: [[Pazar, Rize|Athenae]], [[Arhavi|Archabis]] and [[Sarpi, Georgia|Apsarus]]; Tzanni were neither subjects of the Romans nor of the king of the Lazica, except that during the reign of the [[List of Byzantine emperors|Byzantine emperor]] [[Justinian I]] (r. 527\u2013565) they were subdued, [[Christianization|Christianized]] and brought to central rule.<ref>{{harvnb|Evans|2000|p=93}}.</ref><ref>[[Procopius]] ''Bell. Pers''. i. 15, ''Bell. Goth''. iv. 2, ''de Aed.'' iii. 6.</ref> Tzanni began to have closer contact with the Greeks and acquired various [[Culture of Greece|Hellenic]] cultural traits. The bishops of the [[Exarchate of Lazica|Lazica]] appointed their priests, seeing they are Christians.\n[[File:Map_of_the_Caucasus,_740_CE.svg|thumb|Map of the Caucasus, {{circa|740 AD}}]]\nFrom 542 to 562, Lazica was a scene of the protracted rivalry between the [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman]] and [[Sasanian Empire|Sassanid]] empires, culminating in the [[Lazic War]], where 1,000 Tzanni auxiliaries under [[Dagisthaeus]] participated. Emperor [[Heraclius]]'s offensive in 628 AD brought victory over the Persians and ensured Roman predominance in Lazica until the invasion and conquest of the Caucasus by the [[Rashidun Caliphate|Arabs]] in the second half of the seventh century. As the result of Muslim invasions, the ancient [[Metropolis (religious jurisdiction)|metropolis]], [[Phasis (titular see)|Phasis]], was lost and Trebizond became the new Metropolitan bishop of Lazica, since then the name Lazi appears the general Greek name for Tzanni. According to Geography of [[Anania Shirakatsi]] of the 7th century,<ref>Ashkharatsuyts, Long Recension, V, 19.</ref> Colchis (''Yeger'' in Armenian sources, same as Lazica) was subdivided into four small districts, one of them being Tzanica, that is [[Chaldia]], and mentions Athinae, Rhizus and Trebizond among its cities. From the second half of the eight century the Trebizond area is referred to in Greek sources (namely of [[Epiphanius of Constantinople]]) as Lazica. The 10th-century Arab geographer [[Abu'l-Fida|Abul Feda]] regards city of Trebizond as being largely a Lazian port.\n\nIn 780, [[kingdom of Abkhazia]] incorporated the former territories of Lazica via a dynastic succession, thus ousting the Pontic Lazs (formerly known as Tzanni) from western Georgia; thereafter, the Tzanni lived under nominal Byzantine suzerainty in the [[Theme (Byzantine district)|theme]] of Chaldia, with its capital at Trebizond, governed by the native semi-autonomous rulers, like the [[Gabras]] family,<ref name=\"Hewsen47\">Hewsen, 47</ref> of possibly \"Greco-Laz\" or simply [[Chalybes|Chaldian]] origin.<ref>A. Bryer and D. Winfield, ''\u03a4he Byzantine Monuments and Topography of the Pontos'',  pp.300</ref>\n[[File:Trebizond1300.png|thumb|Map of the [[Empire of Trebizond|Trebizond Empire]] in Anatolia, {{circa|1300}}]]\nWith the [[Georgian expedition to Chaldia|Georgian intervention in Chaldia]] and [[Fourth Crusade|collapse of Byzantine Empire]] in 1204, [[Empire of Trebizond]] was established along the southeastern coast of the Black Sea, populated by a large Kartvelian-speaking population.<ref name=\"Mikaberidze, A. (2015).2\">Mikaberidze, A. (2015). Historical dictionary of Georgia. 2nd ed. Lanham, MD, United States: ROWMAN & LITTLEFIELD, p.634.</ref> In the eastern part of the same empire, an autonomous coastal theme of [[Lazia (Pontus)|Greater Lazia]] was established.<ref>Thys-\u015eenocak, Lucienne. ''Ottoman Women Builders''. Aldershot, England: Ashgate, 2006.</ref> Byzantine authors, such as [[George Pachymeres|Pachymeres]], and to some extent Trapezuntines such as [[John Lazaropoulos|Lazaropoulos]] and [[Basilios Bessarion|Bessarion]], regarded the Trapezuntian Empire as being no more than a Lazian border state.<ref>Bryer 1967, 179.</ref> Byzantine emperors, as well as Byzantine authors, such as [[George Pachymeres]], [[Nicephorus Gregoras]] and to some extent Trapezuntines such as [[John Lazaropoulos]] and [[Basilios Bessarion]], regarded the [[List of Trapezuntine emperors|emperors of Trebizond]] as the \u201cprinces of the Lazes\u201d, while the possession of these \"princes\" was also called Lazica,<ref>Karl von Hahn, \u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0434\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0433\u0440\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438 \u0440\u0438\u043c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u043e \u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0435, II, pp. 205, 206, 207, 208, 209, 210</ref> in other words, their state was known as the Principality of the Lazes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The foundation of the Empire of Trebizond 1204-1222|author=Vasil\u02b9ev, A. A.|date=1936|publisher=Medieval Academy of America|oclc=43154237}}</ref> Though Greek in higher culture, the rural areas of Trebizond empire appear to have been predominantly Laz in ethnic composition.<ref>[https://www.encyclopedia.com/humanities/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/laz Encyclopedia of World Cultures, Laz]</ref> Laz family names, with [[Hellenization|Hellenized]] terminations, are noticeable in the records of the mediaeval empire of Trebizond, and it is perhaps not too venturesome to suggest that the [[Trapezuntine Civil War|antagonism]] between the \"town-party\" and the \"country-party\" which existed in the politics of \"the Empire,\" was in fact a national antagonism of Laz against Greek.<ref>ROYAL GEOGRAPHICAL SOCIETY (GREAT BRITAIN). (1893). The Geographical journal. London, Royal Geographical Society.</ref>\n\nIn 1282, Trebizond was [[Siege of Trebizond (1282)|besieged]] by [[Kingdom of Imereti]], however after the failed attempt to take the city, the Georgians occupied several provinces,<ref name=\"Miller-30\">Miller, ''Trebizond'', p. 30</ref> and all the Trebizontine province of Lazia threw off its allegiance to the king of the 'Iberian' and 'Lazian' tribes.\n\n===  Early Modern era ===\n{{further|Hellenization of Laz people}}\n[[File:Sanjak_of_Lazistan,_Ottoman_Anatolia,_1914.png|thumb|[[Lazistan Sanjak|Sanjak of Lazistan]], Ottoman Anatolia, 1914]]\nLaz populated area was often contested by different Georgian principalities, however through [[Battle of Murjakheti]] in 1535, [[Principality of Guria]] ensured control over it, until 1547, when it was finally [[Ottoman invasion of Guria|conquered]] by resurgent [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] forces and reorganized into the [[Lazistan Sanjak|Lazistan sanjak]] as part of [[eyalet]] of [[Trebizond Eyalet|Trabzon]].\n\nThe Ottomans fought for three centuries to [[Three Hundred Laz Martyrs|destroy]] the Christian-Georgian consciousness of the Laz people.<ref>[http://www.pravoslavie.ru/7245.html HOLY MARTYRS OF LAZETI (17TH\u201318TH CENTURIES)] pravoslavie.ru</ref> Due to the Ottoman [[Islamization]] policy, throughout of seventeenth century Lazs gradually converted to [[Islam]]. As the Ottomans consolidated their rule, the [[Millet (Ottoman Empire)|Millet system]] was brought to the newly conquered territories. Local orthodox inhabitants, once subordinated to the [[Georgian Orthodox Church]], had to obey [[Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople|Patriarchate of Constantinople]],<ref name=\"nplg.gov.ge\">[http://www.nplg.gov.ge/gsdl/cgi-bin/library.exe?e=d-01000-00---off-0patriarc--00-1----0-10-0---0---0prompt-10---4-------0-1l--11-ka-50---20-about---00-3-1-00-0-0-11-1-0utfZz-8-00&a=d&cl=CL3&d=HASHda05345f254c8b87205372.6.4 \u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10d7\u10d0 \u10d3\u10d4\u10dc\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10dd\u10dc\u10d0\u10da\u10d8\u10d6\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10d0 XVII-XX \u10e1\u10d0\u10e3\u10d9\u10e3\u10dc\u10d4\u10d4\u10d1\u10e8\u10d8; \u10da\u10d0\u10d6\u10d4\u10d7\u10d8-\u10d7\u10e0\u10d8\u10d0\u10da\u10d4\u10d7\u10d8 (\u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10d7\u10d0 \u10d2\u10d0\u10d1\u10d4\u10e0\u10eb\u10dc\u10d4\u10d1\u10d0)] [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]] of Manglisi, [[Ananias (Jafaridze)|Ananias Japaridze]], nplg.gov.ge</ref> thus gradually becoming [[Pontic Greeks|Greeks]], the process known as [[Hellenization of Laz people]].<ref name=\"nplg.gov.ge\" /> Lazs who were under the control of Constantinople, soon lost their language and self-identity as they became Greeks and learned Greek,<ref>{{cite book|title=\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043e\u043a \u0432 \u0413\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u0438.|author=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a \u042e\u043d\u0433\u0435, \u0411\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0434 \u0411\u043e\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0447|publisher=\u0410\u0418\u0420\u041e-XXI|year=2015|isbn=978-5-91022-306-0|location=Moscow|pages=93|quote=There are orthodox Lazs who are under the control of the Greek patriarchate in Istanbul. They speak Greek and call themselves Greeks.}}</ref> especially [[Pontic Greek|Pontic dialect]] of [[Greek language]], although native language was preserved by Lazs who had become Muslims. In the middle of the seventeen century, several governors of [[Tunis]], who bore the title of [[Dey]] were Laz origin, such as: Muhammad Laz (1647-1653), Mustafa Laz (1653-1665) and Ali Laz (1673).\n\nNot only the [[Pasha]]s (governors) of Trabzon until the 19th century, but real authority in many of the ''[[Kaza|cazas]]'' (districts) of each sanjak by the mid-17th century lay in the hands of relatively independent native Laz [[derebey]]s (\"valley-lords\"), or feudal chiefs who exercised absolute authority in their own districts, carried on petty warfare with each other, did not owe allegiance to a superior and never paid contributions to the sultan. In the period following the war of 1828\u20131829, [[Mahmud II|Sultan Mahmud II]] attempted to break the power of the great independent derebeys of Lazistan. In the event, the Laz derebeys, led by [[Tahir A\u011fa Tuzcuo\u011flu]] of Rize, did rise in [[Laz rebellion (1832\u20131834)|revolt]] in 1832. The revolt was initially successful: at its height in January 1833, but by the spring of 1834, the rising had been put down.<ref name=\"Adjar\">{{cite thesis|type=Thesis|last=Brody|first=David|date=1999|title=Ajarian identity and the regime of Aslan Abashidze|publisher=Bilkent University}}</ref> The suppression of the rising had finally broken the power of the Laz derebeys. This state of insubordination was not really broken until the assertion of Ottoman authority during the reforms of the [[Osman Nuri Pasha|Osman Pasha]] in the 1850s.\n\nIn 1547, Ottomans built coastal fortress of [[Gonio Fortress|Gonia]], an important Ottoman outpost in southwestern Georgia,<ref name=\"Vakh\">{{cite book|url=http://dspace.nplg.gov.ge/bitstream/1234/3067/1/Istoria_Carstva_Gruzinskogo.pdf|last=Bagrationi|first=Vakhushti|publisher=Metsniereba|year=1976|editor=Nakashidze, N.T.|location=Tbilisi|pages=133\u2013135|language=ru|script-title=ru:\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0426\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0413\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e|trans-title=History of the Kingdom of Georgia|authorlink=Prince Vakhushti of Kartli}}</ref><ref>{{cite thesis|last=Church|first=Kenneth|title=From dynastic principality to imperial district: the incorporation of Guria into the Russian Empire to 1856|date=2001|publisher=University of Michigan|type=Ph.D.|pages=127\u2013129}}</ref> which initially served as capital of Lazistan; then [[Batumi|Batum]] until it was acquired according to the [[Reinsurance Treaty|Congress of Berlin]] by the Russians in 1878, throughout the [[Russo-Turkish War (1877\u20131878)|Russo-Turkish War]], thereafter, [[Rize]] became the capital of the sanjak. The Muslim Lazs living in newly established [[Batum Oblast|Batumi Oblast]] were subjected to ethnic cleansing; by 1882, approximately 40,000 Lazs had settled in the Ottoman Empire, especially to provinces in Western Anatolia such as [[Bursa]], [[Yalova]], [[Karam\u00fcrsel|Karamursel]], [[\u0130zmit|Izmit]], [[Adapazar\u0131]] and [[Sapanca]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sarigil|first=Zeki|year=2012|title=Ethnic Groups at 'Critical Junctures': The Laz vs. Kurds|journal=Middle Eastern Studies|volume=48|issue=2|pages=269\u2013286|doi=10.1080/00263206.2011.652778|issn=0026-3206|hdl=11693/12314}}</ref> With the spread of [[Young Turks|Young Turk movement]] in Lazistan, the short-lived autonomist national movement headed by [[Faik Efendishi|Faik Efendi\u015fi]] was established. However, it was soon eliminated as the result of [[Abdul Hamid II|Abdul Hamid]]'s intervention.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2014|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0415.\u041f. \u041f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043e\u043a \u0432 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0438 \u0444\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435: \u0441\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0445\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430. \u041f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043e\u043a|journal=\u0410\u043a\u0442\u0443\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u044b \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0430|volume=5|issue=5|pages=975\u2013981|doi=10.7256/1994-1471.2014.5.9758|issn=1994-1471}}</ref>\n[[File:AsiaMinor1910.jpg|thumb|Ethnic map of Asia Minor, 1910]]\nDuring the [[World War I|First World War]] (1914\u201318) Russians invaded the provinces of Rize and Trabzon. Several thousand Lazs were slaughtered during the campaign led by the Russian general [[Vladimir Liakhov|Vladimir Lyakhov]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Between Two Empires : Ahmet Agaoglu and the New Turkey.|last=Shissler, A. Holly.|date=2014|publisher=I.B. Tauris|isbn=9780857710840|oclc=1055598134}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Caucasus : an introduction|last=De Waal, Thomas.|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195399769|oclc=490810956}}</ref> as a punishment for their pro-Turkish orientation. However, following the [[October Revolution|Bolshevik Revolution]] in 1917, the Russian forces had to withdraw from the region and finally left the area to the Ottoman-Turkish forces in March 1918. From 1918 to 1920, the national movement swept rapidly all around Lazistan, committees and an interim government was created. It was oriented towards Soviet Russia. But as soon as, the Soviet-Turkish [[Treaty of Moscow (1921)|treaty of friendship]] was concluded, it helped the Turks, to integrate Lazistan.<ref name=\":1\" /> The autonomous Lazistan sanjak existed until 1923, while the designation of the term of Lazistan was officially banned in 1926, by the [[Kemalism|Kemalists]].<ref name=\"Thys-\u015eenocak, Lucienne 20062\">Thys-\u015eenocak, Lucienne. Ottoman Women Builders. Aldershot, England: Ashgate, 2006. Print.</ref> Lazistan was divided between [[Rize Province|Rize]] and [[Artvin Province|Artvin]] provinces.\n\nAt the beginning of the [[Stalinism|Stalinist era]], the Lazs living under Soviet domination had a certain cultural autonomy in the Soviet Union, but after the [[World War II|Second World War]], Soviet authorities designed a strategy to clean the border region from so-called unreliable elements. Laz population was sent to exile in [[Siberia]] and [[Central Asia|Centrall Asia]]. The political climate had changed after the death of Stalin in 1953, and between 1953 and 1957, all Lazs who had been deported returned to the homeland.\n\n=== Modern ===\nMost Laz people today live in Turkey, but the Laz minority group has no official status in Turkey. The number of the Laz speakers is decreasing, and is now limited chiefly to the Rize and Artvin areas.\n\n==== Self-identification ====\nOver time the Laz living on either side of the frontier have developed different conceptions of what it means to be Laz. Today, most of those living in Turkey do consider themselves Turkish.<ref>[https://chai-khana.org/en/the-laz-two-tales-of-one-people Chai-khana.org; ''The Laz: Two Tales of One People'' , Irakli Dzneladze]</ref> In contrast, Laz identity in Georgia has largely merged with a Georgian identity, and the meaning of \"Laz\" is seen as merely a regional category.<ref>Minorsky, V. \"Laz.\" Encyclopaedia of Islam, Second Edition. Edited by: P. Bearman , Th. Bianquis , C.E . Bosworth , E. van Donzel and W.P. Heinrichs. Brill, 2010.,</ref> At the same time, in Turkey, the term Laz is a 'folk' definition for people of different ethnic and linguistic backgrounds originating from the [[Black Sea Region]]. Officially, the Laz people are not recognized as a minority. Thus, many Turks do not even know about their diverse existence and falsely call the inhabitants of the Black Sea coast as the \"Lazlar\". Within the last decade more and more intellectual Laz people realized that the disappearance of their language would lead to the disappearance of their identity and tried to preserve their inherited culture through political empowerment, linguistic education, and music and poetry.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://lazkulturdernegi.org.tr Laz Culture Association] (Turkish)\n* [http://www.lazca.org Lazca.org: Culture, News and Information] (Turkish)\n* [http://www.lazebura.com Lazebura.com: Culture, News and Information] (Turkish)\n* [http://www.lazuri.com Lazuri.com: Culture Portal] (Turkish)\n\n[[Category:Laz people| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Laz people}}\nThe '''Laz people''' or '''Lazi''' ({{lang-ka|\u10da\u10d0\u10d6\u10d8}}, {{lang|ka-Latn|lazi}}; or {{lang|ka|\u10ed\u10d0\u10dc\u10d8}}, {{lang|ka-Latn|ch'ani}}; {{lang-tr|Laz}}) are an indigenous [[Kartvelian languages|Kartvelian]]-speaking [[ethnic group]]<ref name=\"ethno\">{{cite book|title=An Ethnohistorical Dictionary of the Russian and Soviet Empires|author=James S. Olson|publisher=Greenwood|year=1994|editors=Lee Brigance Pappas, Nicholas Charles Pappas|page=436|author-link=James S. Olson}}</ref> inhabiting [[Lazistan]], which today encompasses parts of [[Black Sea]] coastal regions of [[Black Sea Region|Turkey]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref>1 Minorsky, V. \"Laz.\" Encyclopaedia of Islam, Second Edition. Edited by: P. Bearman , Th. Bianquis , C.E . Bosworth , E. van Donzel and W.P. Heinrichs. Brill, 2010.</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Antiquity ===\n[[File:M\u00d6_6._y\u00fczy\u0131la_ait_g\u00fcm\u00fc\u015f_Kolkhis_sikkesi.jpg|left|thumb|[[Colchis|Colchian]] silver coin, 6th century BC]]\nIn the thirteenth century [[Common Era|BC]], the Kingdom of [[Colchis]] was formed as a result of the increasing consolidation of the tribes inhabiting the region, which covered modern western Georgia and [[Turkey]]'s north-eastern provinces of [[Trabzon Province|Trabzon]], [[Rize Province|Rize]] and [[Artvin Province|Artvin]].<ref name=\"Andrew Andersen p. 91\">Andrew Andersen, History of Ancient Caucasus, p.&nbsp;91</ref> Colchis was an important region in Black Sea trade \u2013 rich with gold, wax, hemp, and honey. In the eighth century, several Greek [[Colonies in antiquity|trading colonies]] were established along the shores of the Black Sea, one of them being Trebizond ({{lang-el|\u03a4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c0\u03b5\u03b6\u03bf\u1fe6\u03c2|Trapezous}}) founded by [[Milesians (Greek)|Milesian]] traders from [[Sinop, Turkey|Sinope]] in 756 BC. Trebizond's trade partners included the Proto-Laz tribes of [[Mossynoeci]].\n[[File:Ethnic_Caucasia-en.png|alt=|thumb|Ethnic map of the [[Caucasus]] in the 5th and 4th centuries BC]]\nBy the sixth century BC, the tribes living in the southern Colchis ([[Macrones]], [[Mossynoeci]], [[Marres]] etc.) were incorporated into the [[Nineteenth Satrapy|nineteenth satrapy]] of [[Achaemenid Empire|Persia]]. The Achaemenid Empire was defeated by [[Alexander the Great]], however following the Alexander's death a number of separate kingdoms were established in [[Anatolia]], including [[Kingdom of Pontus|Pontus]], in the corner of the southern Black Sea, ruled by the Persian nobleman [[Mithridates I of Pontus|Mithridates I]]. Culturally, the kingdom was [[Hellenization|Hellenized]],<ref>Children of Achilles: The Greeks in Asia Minor Since the Days of Troy, by John Freely, p. 69\u201370</ref> with Greek as the official language.<ref>The Foreign Policy of Mithridates VI Eupator, King of Pontus, by B.{{nbsp}}C. McGing, p. 11</ref> [[Mithridates VI of Pontus|Mithridates VI]] conquered the Colchis, and gave it to his son [[Mithridates of Colchis]].\n\nAs a result of the brilliant [[Mithridatic Wars|Roman campaigns]] between 88-63 BC, led by the generals [[Pompey]] and [[Lucullus]], the kingdom of Pontus was completely destroyed by the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] and all its territory, including Colchis, was incorporated into the Roman Empire. The former southern provinces of Colchis were reorganized into the [[Roman province]] of [[Pontus (region)|Pontus Polemoniacus]], while the northern Cholchis became the Roman province of [[Georgia in the Roman era|Lazicum]]. Roman control remained likewise only nominal over the tribes of the interior.<ref name=\"Talbert1226\">{{harvnb|Talbert|2000|p=1226}}.</ref>\n\nThe first-century historians [[Memnon of Heraclea|Memnon]] and [[Strabo]] remark in passing that the people formerly called Macrones bore in his day the name of [[Sanni]], a claim supported also by [[Stephanus of Byzantium]]. The second-century historian [[Arrian]] notes that [[Zans|Tzanni]], same as the Sanni<ref>[[Procopius]], ''History of the Wars'', I-II [21-25]</ref> are neighbours of the Colchians, while the latter were now referred to as the Lazi. By the mid-third century, the Lazi tribe came to dominate most of Colchis, establishing the [[Lazica|kingdom of Lazica]].\n\n=== Middle Ages ===\n[[File:Lazica_in_Late_Antiquity.svg|left|thumb|The kingdom of Lazica in late antiquity]]\nThe warlike tribes of the Chaldia, called Tzanni, the ancestors of modern Laz people lived in ''Tzanica'', the area located between the Byzantine and the Lazica. It included several settlements named: [[Pazar, Rize|Athenae]], [[Arhavi|Archabis]] and [[Sarpi, Georgia|Apsarus]]; Tzanni were neither subjects of the Romans nor of the king of the Lazica, except that during the reign of the [[List of Byzantine emperors|Byzantine emperor]] [[Justinian I]] (r. 527\u2013565) they were subdued, [[Christianization|Christianized]] and brought to central rule.<ref>{{harvnb|Evans|2000|p=93}}.</ref><ref>[[Procopius]] ''Bell. Pers''. i. 15, ''Bell. Goth''. iv. 2, ''de Aed.'' iii. 6.</ref> Tzanni began to have closer contact with the Greeks and acquired various [[Culture of Greece|Hellenic]] cultural traits. The bishops of the [[Exarchate of Lazica|Lazica]] appointed their priests, seeing they are Christians.\n[[File:Map_of_the_Caucasus,_740_CE.svg|thumb|Map of the Caucasus, {{circa|740 AD}}]]\nFrom 542 to 562, Lazica was a scene of the protracted rivalry between the [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman]] and [[Sasanian Empire|Sassanid]] empires, culminating in the [[Lazic War]], where 1,000 Tzanni auxiliaries under [[Dagisthaeus]] participated. Emperor [[Heraclius]]'s offensive in 628 AD brought victory over the Persians and ensured Roman predominance in Lazica until the invasion and conquest of the Caucasus by the [[Rashidun Caliphate|Arabs]] in the second half of the seventh century. As the result of Muslim invasions, the ancient [[Metropolis (religious jurisdiction)|metropolis]], [[Phasis (titular see)|Phasis]], was lost and Trebizond became the new Metropolitan bishop of Lazica, since then the name Lazi appears the general Greek name for Tzanni. According to Geography of [[Anania Shirakatsi]] of the 7th century,<ref>Ashkharatsuyts, Long Recension, V, 19.</ref> Colchis (''Yeger'' in Armenian sources, same as Lazica) was subdivided into four small districts, one of them being Tzanica, that is [[Chaldia]], and mentions Athinae, Rhizus and Trebizond among its cities. From the second half of the eight century the Trebizond area is referred to in Greek sources (namely of [[Epiphanius of Constantinople]]) as Lazica. The 10th-century Arab geographer [[Abu'l-Fida|Abul Feda]] regards city of Trebizond as being largely a Lazian port.\n\nIn 780, [[kingdom of Abkhazia]] incorporated the former territories of Lazica via a dynastic succession, thus ousting the Pontic Lazs (formerly known as Tzanni) from western Georgia; thereafter, the Tzanni lived under nominal Byzantine suzerainty in the [[Theme (Byzantine district)|theme]] of Chaldia, with its capital at Trebizond, governed by the native semi-autonomous rulers, like the [[Gabras]] family,<ref name=\"Hewsen47\">Hewsen, 47</ref> of possibly \"Greco-Laz\" or simply [[Chalybes|Chaldian]] origin.<ref>A. Bryer and D. Winfield, ''\u03a4he Byzantine Monuments and Topography of the Pontos'',  pp.300</ref>\n[[File:Trebizond1300.png|thumb|Map of the [[Empire of Trebizond|Trebizond Empire]] in Anatolia, {{circa|1300}}]]\nWith the [[Georgian expedition to Chaldia|Georgian intervention in Chaldia]] and [[Fourth Crusade|collapse of Byzantine Empire]] in 1204, [[Empire of Trebizond]] was established along the southeastern coast of the Black Sea, populated by a large Kartvelian-speaking population.<ref name=\"Mikaberidze, A. (2015).2\">Mikaberidze, A. (2015). Historical dictionary of Georgia. 2nd ed. Lanham, MD, United States: ROWMAN & LITTLEFIELD, p.634.</ref> In the eastern part of the same empire, an autonomous coastal theme of [[Lazia (Pontus)|Greater Lazia]] was established.<ref>Thys-\u015eenocak, Lucienne. ''Ottoman Women Builders''. Aldershot, England: Ashgate, 2006.</ref> Byzantine authors, such as [[George Pachymeres|Pachymeres]], and to some extent Trapezuntines such as [[John Lazaropoulos|Lazaropoulos]] and [[Basilios Bessarion|Bessarion]], regarded the Trapezuntian Empire as being no more than a Lazian border state.<ref>Bryer 1967, 179.</ref> Byzantine emperors, as well as Byzantine authors, such as [[George Pachymeres]], [[Nicephorus Gregoras]] and to some extent Trapezuntines such as [[John Lazaropoulos]] and [[Basilios Bessarion]], regarded the [[List of Trapezuntine emperors|emperors of Trebizond]] as the \u201cprinces of the Lazes\u201d, while the possession of these \"princes\" was also called Lazica,<ref>Karl von Hahn, \u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0434\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0433\u0440\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438 \u0440\u0438\u043c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u043e \u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0435, II, pp. 205, 206, 207, 208, 209, 210</ref> in other words, their state was known as the Principality of the Lazes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The foundation of the Empire of Trebizond 1204-1222|author=Vasil\u02b9ev, A. A.|date=1936|publisher=Medieval Academy of America|oclc=43154237}}</ref> Though Greek in higher culture, the rural areas of Trebizond empire appear to have been predominantly Laz in ethnic composition.<ref>[https://www.encyclopedia.com/humanities/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/laz Encyclopedia of World Cultures, Laz]</ref> Laz family names, with [[Hellenization|Hellenized]] terminations, are noticeable in the records of the mediaeval empire of Trebizond, and it is perhaps not too venturesome to suggest that the [[Trapezuntine Civil War|antagonism]] between the \"town-party\" and the \"country-party\" which existed in the politics of \"the Empire,\" was in fact a national antagonism of Laz against Greek.<ref>ROYAL GEOGRAPHICAL SOCIETY (GREAT BRITAIN). (1893). The Geographical journal. London, Royal Geographical Society.</ref>\n\nIn 1282, Trebizond was [[Siege of Trebizond (1282)|besieged]] by [[Kingdom of Imereti]], however after the failed attempt to take the city, the Georgians occupied several provinces,<ref name=\"Miller-30\">Miller, ''Trebizond'', p. 30</ref> and all the Trebizontine province of Lazia threw off its allegiance to the king of the 'Iberian' and 'Lazian' tribes.\n\n===  Early Modern era ===\n{{further|Hellenization of Laz people}}\n[[File:Sanjak_of_Lazistan,_Ottoman_Anatolia,_1914.png|thumb|[[Lazistan Sanjak|Sanjak of Lazistan]], Ottoman Anatolia, 1914]]\nLaz populated area was often contested by different Georgian principalities, however through [[Battle of Murjakheti]] in 1535, [[Principality of Guria]] ensured control over it, until 1547, when it was finally [[Ottoman invasion of Guria|conquered]] by resurgent [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] forces and reorganized into the [[Lazistan Sanjak|Lazistan sanjak]] as part of [[eyalet]] of [[Trebizond Eyalet|Trabzon]].\n\nThe Ottomans fought for three centuries to [[Three Hundred Laz Martyrs|destroy]] the Christian-Georgian consciousness of the Laz people.<ref>[http://www.pravoslavie.ru/7245.html HOLY MARTYRS OF LAZETI (17TH\u201318TH CENTURIES)] pravoslavie.ru</ref> Due to the Ottoman [[Islamization]] policy, throughout of seventeenth century Lazs gradually converted to [[Islam]]. As the Ottomans consolidated their rule, the [[Millet (Ottoman Empire)|Millet system]] was brought to the newly conquered territories. Local orthodox inhabitants, once subordinated to the [[Georgian Orthodox Church]], had to obey [[Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople|Patriarchate of Constantinople]],<ref name=\"nplg.gov.ge\">[http://www.nplg.gov.ge/gsdl/cgi-bin/library.exe?e=d-01000-00---off-0patriarc--00-1----0-10-0---0---0prompt-10---4-------0-1l--11-ka-50---20-about---00-3-1-00-0-0-11-1-0utfZz-8-00&a=d&cl=CL3&d=HASHda05345f254c8b87205372.6.4 \u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10d7\u10d0 \u10d3\u10d4\u10dc\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10dd\u10dc\u10d0\u10da\u10d8\u10d6\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10d0 XVII-XX \u10e1\u10d0\u10e3\u10d9\u10e3\u10dc\u10d4\u10d4\u10d1\u10e8\u10d8; \u10da\u10d0\u10d6\u10d4\u10d7\u10d8-\u10d7\u10e0\u10d8\u10d0\u10da\u10d4\u10d7\u10d8 (\u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10d7\u10d0 \u10d2\u10d0\u10d1\u10d4\u10e0\u10eb\u10dc\u10d4\u10d1\u10d0)] [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]] of Manglisi, [[Ananias (Jafaridze)|Ananias Japaridze]], nplg.gov.ge</ref> thus gradually becoming [[Pontic Greeks|Greeks]], the process known as [[Hellenization of Laz people]].<ref name=\"nplg.gov.ge\" /> Lazs who were under the control of Constantinople, soon lost their language and self-identity as they became Greeks and learned Greek,<ref>{{cite book|title=\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043e\u043a \u0432 \u0413\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u0438.|author=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a \u042e\u043d\u0433\u0435, \u0411\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0434 \u0411\u043e\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0447|publisher=\u0410\u0418\u0420\u041e-XXI|year=2015|isbn=978-5-91022-306-0|location=Moscow|pages=93|quote=There are orthodox Lazs who are under the control of the Greek patriarchate in Istanbul. They speak Greek and call themselves Greeks.}}</ref> especially [[Pontic Greek|Pontic dialect]] of [[Greek language]], although native language was preserved by Lazs who had become Muslims. In the middle of the seventeen century, several governors of [[Tunis]], who bore the title of [[Dey]] were Laz origin, such as: Muhammad Laz (1647-1653), Mustafa Laz (1653-1665) and Ali Laz (1673).\n\nNot only the [[Pasha]]s (governors) of Trabzon until the 19th century, but real authority in many of the ''[[Kaza|cazas]]'' (districts) of each sanjak by the mid-17th century lay in the hands of relatively independent native Laz [[derebey]]s (\"valley-lords\"), or feudal chiefs who exercised absolute authority in their own districts, carried on petty warfare with each other, did not owe allegiance to a superior and never paid contributions to the sultan. In the period following the war of 1828\u20131829, [[Mahmud II|Sultan Mahmud II]] attempted to break the power of the great independent derebeys of Lazistan. In the event, the Laz derebeys, led by [[Tahir A\u011fa Tuzcuo\u011flu]] of Rize, did rise in [[Laz rebellion (1832\u20131834)|revolt]] in 1832. The revolt was initially successful: at its height in January 1833, but by the spring of 1834, the rising had been put down.<ref name=\"Adjar\">{{cite thesis|type=Thesis|last=Brody|first=David|date=1999|title=Ajarian identity and the regime of Aslan Abashidze|publisher=Bilkent University}}</ref> The suppression of the rising had finally broken the power of the Laz derebeys. This state of insubordination was not really broken until the assertion of Ottoman authority during the reforms of the [[Osman Nuri Pasha|Osman Pasha]] in the 1850s.\n\nIn 1547, Ottomans built coastal fortress of [[Gonio Fortress|Gonia]], an important Ottoman outpost in southwestern Georgia,<ref name=\"Vakh\">{{cite book|url=http://dspace.nplg.gov.ge/bitstream/1234/3067/1/Istoria_Carstva_Gruzinskogo.pdf|last=Bagrationi|first=Vakhushti|publisher=Metsniereba|year=1976|editor=Nakashidze, N.T.|location=Tbilisi|pages=133\u2013135|language=ru|script-title=ru:\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0426\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0413\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e|trans-title=History of the Kingdom of Georgia|authorlink=Prince Vakhushti of Kartli}}</ref><ref>{{cite thesis|last=Church|first=Kenneth|title=From dynastic principality to imperial district: the incorporation of Guria into the Russian Empire to 1856|date=2001|publisher=University of Michigan|type=Ph.D.|pages=127\u2013129}}</ref> which initially served as capital of Lazistan; then [[Batumi|Batum]] until it was acquired according to the [[Reinsurance Treaty|Congress of Berlin]] by the Russians in 1878, throughout the [[Russo-Turkish War (1877\u20131878)|Russo-Turkish War]], thereafter, [[Rize]] became the capital of the sanjak. The Muslim Lazs living in newly established [[Batum Oblast|Batumi Oblast]] were subjected to ethnic cleansing; by 1882, approximately 40,000 Lazs had settled in the Ottoman Empire, especially to provinces in Western Anatolia such as [[Bursa]], [[Yalova]], [[Karam\u00fcrsel|Karamursel]], [[\u0130zmit|Izmit]], [[Adapazar\u0131]] and [[Sapanca]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sarigil|first=Zeki|year=2012|title=Ethnic Groups at 'Critical Junctures': The Laz vs. Kurds|journal=Middle Eastern Studies|volume=48|issue=2|pages=269\u2013286|doi=10.1080/00263206.2011.652778|issn=0026-3206|hdl=11693/12314}}</ref> With the spread of [[Young Turks|Young Turk movement]] in Lazistan, the short-lived autonomist national movement headed by [[Faik Efendishi|Faik Efendi\u015fi]] was established. However, it was soon eliminated as the result of [[Abdul Hamid II|Abdul Hamid]]'s intervention.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2014|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0415.\u041f. \u041f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043e\u043a \u0432 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0438 \u0444\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435: \u0441\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0445\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430. \u041f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043e\u043a|journal=\u0410\u043a\u0442\u0443\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u044b \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0430|volume=5|issue=5|pages=975\u2013981|doi=10.7256/1994-1471.2014.5.9758|issn=1994-1471}}</ref>\n[[File:AsiaMinor1910.jpg|thumb|Ethnic map of Asia Minor, 1910]]\nDuring the [[World War I|First World War]] (1914\u201318) Russians invaded the provinces of Rize and Trabzon. Several thousand Lazs were slaughtered during the campaign led by the Russian general [[Vladimir Liakhov|Vladimir Lyakhov]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Between Two Empires : Ahmet Agaoglu and the New Turkey.|last=Shissler, A. Holly.|date=2014|publisher=I.B. Tauris|isbn=9780857710840|oclc=1055598134}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Caucasus : an introduction|last=De Waal, Thomas.|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195399769|oclc=490810956}}</ref> as a punishment for their pro-Turkish orientation. However, following the [[October Revolution|Bolshevik Revolution]] in 1917, the Russian forces had to withdraw from the region and finally left the area to the Ottoman-Turkish forces in March 1918. From 1918 to 1920, the national movement swept rapidly all around Lazistan, committees and an interim government was created. It was oriented towards Soviet Russia. But as soon as, the Soviet-Turkish [[Treaty of Moscow (1921)|treaty of friendship]] was concluded, it helped the Turks, to integrate Lazistan.<ref name=\":1\" /> The autonomous Lazistan sanjak existed until 1923, while the designation of the term of Lazistan was officially banned in 1926, by the [[Kemalism|Kemalists]].<ref name=\"Thys-\u015eenocak, Lucienne 20062\">Thys-\u015eenocak, Lucienne. Ottoman Women Builders. Aldershot, England: Ashgate, 2006. Print.</ref> Lazistan was divided between [[Rize Province|Rize]] and [[Artvin Province|Artvin]] provinces.\n\nAt the beginning of the [[Stalinism|Stalinist era]], the Lazs living under Soviet domination had a certain cultural autonomy in the Soviet Union, but after the [[World War II|Second World War]], Soviet authorities designed a strategy to clean the border region from so-called unreliable elements. Laz population was sent to exile in [[Siberia]] and [[Central Asia|Centrall Asia]]. The political climate had changed after the death of Stalin in 1953, and between 1953 and 1957, all Lazs who had been deported returned to the homeland.\n\n=== Modern ===\nMost Laz people today live in Turkey, but the Laz minority group has no official status in Turkey. The number of the Laz speakers is decreasing, and is now limited chiefly to the Rize and Artvin areas.\n\n==== Self-identification ====\nOver time the Laz living on either side of the frontier have developed different conceptions of what it means to be Laz. Today, most of those living in Turkey do not consider themselves Turkish, but uphold their Laz identity as a separate one.<ref>[https://chai-khana.org/en/the-laz-two-tales-of-one-people Chai-khana.org; ''The Laz: Two Tales of One People'' , Irakli Dzneladze]</ref> In contrast, Laz identity in Georgia has largely merged with a Georgian identity, and the meaning of \"Laz\" is seen as merely a regional category.<ref>Minorsky, V. \"Laz.\" Encyclopaedia of Islam, Second Edition. Edited by: P. Bearman , Th. Bianquis , C.E . Bosworth , E. van Donzel and W.P. Heinrichs. Brill, 2010.,</ref> At the same time, in Turkey, the term Laz is a 'folk' definition for people of different ethnic and linguistic backgrounds originating from the [[Black Sea Region]]. Officially, the Laz people are not recognized as a minority. Thus, many Turks do not even know about their diverse existence and falsely call the inhabitants of the Black Sea coast as the \"Lazlar\". Within the last decade more and more intellectual Laz people realized that the disappearance of their language would lead to the disappearance of their identity and tried to preserve their inherited culture through political empowerment, linguistic education, and music and poetry.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://lazkulturdernegi.org.tr Laz Culture Association] (Turkish)\n* [http://www.lazca.org Lazca.org: Culture, News and Information] (Turkish)\n* [http://www.lazebura.com Lazebura.com: Culture, News and Information] (Turkish)\n* [http://www.lazuri.com Lazuri.com: Culture Portal] (Turkish)\n\n[[Category:Laz people| ]]\n", "name_user": "77.22.179.19", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSelf-identification)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Laz_people"}
{"title_page": "Moonton", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = MOONYON BODOH\n| logo                = \n| image               = Moonton1.png\n| type                = Private\n| industry            = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded             = 2014\n| founders            = Justin Yuan\n| hq_location_city    = [[Minhang District]], [[Shanghai]]<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|title=About MOONTON|url=https://www.moonton.com/#/company|website=MOONTON|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n| hq_location_country = China\n| num_locations       = \n| num_locations_year  = \n| key_people          = {{unbulleted list|Justin Yuan (CEO)|Xu Zhen Hua (CEO)}}\n| products            = {{Unbulleted list|''Magic Rush: Heroes''|''[[Mobile Legends: Bang Bang]]''|''Mobile Legends: Adventure''}}\n| num_employees       = 300+<ref>{{cite news|author=ABS-CBN Sports|title=Philippine teams to compete in the first ever Mobile Legends: Bang Bang World Championship 2019|url=https://sports.abs-cbn.com/esports/news/2019/11/11/phi-compete-ml-bang-bang-world-championships-2019-63165|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=[[ABS-CBN News]]|publisher=[[ABS-CBN|ABS-CBN Corporation]]|date=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n| num_employees_year  = 2019\n| parent              = \n| website             = http://www.moonton.com/\n}}\n'''Moonton''', formally '''YoungJoy Technology Limited''', then '''Shanghai Moonton Technology Co., Ltd.''' ({{zh|c=\u4e0a\u6d77\u6c90\u77b3\u79d1\u6280\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|p=Sh\u00e0ngh\u01cei m\u00f9 t\u00f3ng k\u0113j\u00ec y\u01d2uxi\u00e0n g\u014dngs\u012b}})  is a Chinese [[video game developer]] and [[Video game publisher|publisher]] based in [[Shanghai]], [[China]]. Founded in April 2014, the company is best known for its mobile [[multiplayer online battle arena]] (MOBA) game ''[[Mobile Legends: Bang Bang]]'' (Chinese: \u65e0\u5c3d\u5bf9\u51b3; pinyin: ''W\u00faj\u00ecn du\u00ecju\u00e9'', also known as \u7591\u72af\u89e3\u8bf4; pinyin: ''Y\u00edf\u00e0n ji\u011bshu\u014d''), released in 2016.\n\n==History==\nMoonton was established in April 2014 within the [[Minhang District]] of [[Shanghai]], [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=https://www.moonton.com/#/ours?language=en|website=MOONTON|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"About\"/> Its two co-founders are Justin Yuan and Xu Zhen Hua (Watson), who also became partner [[chief executive officer]]s (CEOs) of the company.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sheany|title=Game Developers Should Focus on Each Country's Unique Culture: Moonton Chief Executive|url=https://jakartaglobe.id/context/game-developers-focus-countrys-unique-culture-moonton-chief-executive/|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=[[Jakarta Globe]]|date=9 November 2018|location=[[Nusa Dua]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lanier|first=Liz|title=Tencent Wins Lawsuit Over \u2018League of Legends\u2019 Copycat|url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/riot-games-tencent-wins-lawsuit-league-of-legends-copy-1202878322/|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|date=19 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Fakry Naras Wahidi|title=Fakta Kasus Tencent dan CEO Moonton, Ternyata Bukan Masalah Plagiat |url=http://www.radarempoa.com/2018/07/kasus-tencent-dan-ceo-moonton.html|accessdate=10 January 2020|work=Radarempoa.com |publisher=ONE|date=20 July 2018|language=Indonesian|quote=Setelah tanya rekan yang kebetulan mantan karyawan Moonton, ternyata perusahaan game itu punya dua CEO, yaitu Xu Zhenhua (Watson) dan Justin Yuan.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the company released its first video game, the [[Tower Defense]] (TD) game titled ''Magic Rush: Heroes''.<ref name=\"About\"/> In 2016, the company released the MOBA game ''[[Mobile Legends: Bang Bang]]''.<ref name=\"About\"/> The game became highly popular in Southeast Asia, especially in Myanmar,Malaysia, Indonesia, and Philippines.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harris|first=Iain|title=Moonton\u2019s popular MOBA Mobile Legends plunders $200m in global revenues|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/news/68616/mobile-legends-plunders-200m-in-global-revenues/|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=Pocket Gamer.biz|publisher=Steel Media Ltd.|date=20 July 2018}}</ref> The game is distributed by Elex Tech in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|last=Batchelor|first=James|title=Riot Games suing Chinese developer behind League of Legends clone|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-07-12-riot-games-suing-chinese-developer-behind-league-of-legends-clone|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=gamesindustry.biz|date=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Riot Games]] filed a lawsuit against Moonton, the developer of the mobile game ''Mobile Legends: Bang Bang'', because of copyright infringement, citing similarities between ''Mobile Legends'' and ''[[League of Legends]]''. The case was initially dismissed in California on account of ''[[forum non conveniens]]''. Tencent, on behalf of Riot Games, then filed a new lawsuit in a Chinese court, which ruled in [[Tencent]]'s favor in July 2018, awarding it {{US$|2.9&nbsp;million|long=no}} in damages.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/source-riot-games-parent-tencent-wins-lawsuit-mobile-legends-31079 |title=Riot Games parent Tencent wins $2.9 million in lawsuit against Moonton CEO |first=Aaron |last=Mickunas |date=July 18, 2018 |website=[[Dot Esports]] |access-date=November 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711104720/https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/source-riot-games-parent-tencent-wins-lawsuit-mobile-legends-31079 |archive-date=July 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/riot-games-tencent-wins-lawsuit-league-of-legends-copy-1202878322/ |title=Tencent Wins Lawsuit Over 'League of Legends' Copycat |first=Liz |last=Lanier |date=July 19, 2018 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=November 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330075502/https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/riot-games-tencent-wins-lawsuit-league-of-legends-copy-1202878322/ |archive-date=March 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2014 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of China]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = Moonton\n| logo                = \n| image               = Moonton1.png\n| type                = Private\n| industry            = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded             = 2014\n| founders            = Justin Yuan\n| hq_location_city    = [[Minhang District]], [[Shanghai]]<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|title=About MOONTON|url=https://www.moonton.com/#/company|website=MOONTON|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n| hq_location_country = China\n| num_locations       = \n| num_locations_year  = \n| key_people          = {{unbulleted list|Justin Yuan (CEO)|Xu Zhen Hua (CEO)}}\n| products            = {{Unbulleted list|''Magic Rush: Heroes''|''[[Mobile Legends: Bang Bang]]''|''Mobile Legends: Adventure''}}\n| num_employees       = 300+<ref>{{cite news|author=ABS-CBN Sports|title=Philippine teams to compete in the first ever Mobile Legends: Bang Bang World Championship 2019|url=https://sports.abs-cbn.com/esports/news/2019/11/11/phi-compete-ml-bang-bang-world-championships-2019-63165|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=[[ABS-CBN News]]|publisher=[[ABS-CBN|ABS-CBN Corporation]]|date=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n| num_employees_year  = 2019\n| parent              = \n| website             = http://www.moonton.com/\n}}\n'''Moonton''', formally '''YoungJoy Technology Limited''', then '''Shanghai Moonton Technology Co., Ltd.''' ({{zh|c=\u4e0a\u6d77\u6c90\u77b3\u79d1\u6280\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|p=Sh\u00e0ngh\u01cei m\u00f9 t\u00f3ng k\u0113j\u00ec y\u01d2uxi\u00e0n g\u014dngs\u012b}})  is a Chinese [[video game developer]] and [[Video game publisher|publisher]] based in [[Shanghai]], [[China]]. Founded in April 2014, the company is best known for its mobile [[multiplayer online battle arena]] (MOBA) game ''[[Mobile Legends: Bang Bang]]'' (Chinese: \u65e0\u5c3d\u5bf9\u51b3; pinyin: ''W\u00faj\u00ecn du\u00ecju\u00e9'', also known as \u7591\u72af\u89e3\u8bf4; pinyin: ''Y\u00edf\u00e0n ji\u011bshu\u014d''), released in 2016.\n\n==History==\nMoonton was established in April 2014 within the [[Minhang District]] of [[Shanghai]], [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=https://www.moonton.com/#/ours?language=en|website=MOONTON|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"About\"/> Its two co-founders are Justin Yuan and Xu Zhen Hua (Watson), who also became partner [[chief executive officer]]s (CEOs) of the company.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sheany|title=Game Developers Should Focus on Each Country's Unique Culture: Moonton Chief Executive|url=https://jakartaglobe.id/context/game-developers-focus-countrys-unique-culture-moonton-chief-executive/|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=[[Jakarta Globe]]|date=9 November 2018|location=[[Nusa Dua]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lanier|first=Liz|title=Tencent Wins Lawsuit Over \u2018League of Legends\u2019 Copycat|url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/riot-games-tencent-wins-lawsuit-league-of-legends-copy-1202878322/|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|date=19 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Fakry Naras Wahidi|title=Fakta Kasus Tencent dan CEO Moonton, Ternyata Bukan Masalah Plagiat |url=http://www.radarempoa.com/2018/07/kasus-tencent-dan-ceo-moonton.html|accessdate=10 January 2020|work=Radarempoa.com |publisher=ONE|date=20 July 2018|language=Indonesian|quote=Setelah tanya rekan yang kebetulan mantan karyawan Moonton, ternyata perusahaan game itu punya dua CEO, yaitu Xu Zhenhua (Watson) dan Justin Yuan.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the company released its first video game, the [[Tower Defense]] (TD) game titled ''Magic Rush: Heroes''.<ref name=\"About\"/> In 2016, the company released the MOBA game ''[[Mobile Legends: Bang Bang]]''.<ref name=\"About\"/> The game became highly popular in Southeast Asia, especially in Myanmar,Malaysia, Indonesia, and Philippines.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harris|first=Iain|title=Moonton\u2019s popular MOBA Mobile Legends plunders $200m in global revenues|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/news/68616/mobile-legends-plunders-200m-in-global-revenues/|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=Pocket Gamer.biz|publisher=Steel Media Ltd.|date=20 July 2018}}</ref> The game is distributed by Elex Tech in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|last=Batchelor|first=James|title=Riot Games suing Chinese developer behind League of Legends clone|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-07-12-riot-games-suing-chinese-developer-behind-league-of-legends-clone|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=gamesindustry.biz|date=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Riot Games]] filed a lawsuit against Moonton, the developer of the mobile game ''Mobile Legends: Bang Bang'', because of copyright infringement, citing similarities between ''Mobile Legends'' and ''[[League of Legends]]''. The case was initially dismissed in California on account of ''[[forum non conveniens]]''. Tencent, on behalf of Riot Games, then filed a new lawsuit in a Chinese court, which ruled in [[Tencent]]'s favor in July 2018, awarding it {{US$|2.9&nbsp;million|long=no}} in damages.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/source-riot-games-parent-tencent-wins-lawsuit-mobile-legends-31079 |title=Riot Games parent Tencent wins $2.9 million in lawsuit against Moonton CEO |first=Aaron |last=Mickunas |date=July 18, 2018 |website=[[Dot Esports]] |access-date=November 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711104720/https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/source-riot-games-parent-tencent-wins-lawsuit-mobile-legends-31079 |archive-date=July 11,